<PB REF="2">
<HEAD>THE <HI>Epi&s;tle Dedicatory.</HI> TO THE Right Reverend Father in GOD, Dr. <HI>John Moore,</HI> Lord Bi&s;hop of <HI>ELY.</HI></HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>May it plea&s;e your Lord&s;hip,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>AN indi&s;pen&s;ible Nece&s;&s;ity, obliging me to vindicate my Reputation in the <HI>Knowledge</HI> and <HI>Practi&s;e</HI> of Phy&s;ick, again&s;t the Malicious Calumnies and De|tractions of my <HI>Enemies;</HI> who
<PB REF="3">are only tho&s;e of my own <HI>Pro|fe&s;&s;ion,</HI> and &s;uch as are <HI>unwarily</HI> prejudic'd by their Fal&s;e and Scandalous In&s;inuations; I hope I &s;hall not be charg'd either with <HI>Vanity</HI> or <HI>Ra&s;hne&s;s</HI> in Publi&s;hing the&s;e brief <HI>E&s;&s;ays;</HI> which are de|&s;ign'd for no other end, but that by reading this little <HI>Mannual,</HI> tho&s;e that are Strangers to my Per&s;on, may be convinc'd, that in Studying Phy&s;ick, I have fol|lowed &s;uch Learned Guides and Patterns, by who&s;e Directions and Examples, and my own <HI>Expe|rience,</HI> joined with a tolerable <HI>Capacity,</HI> and an indefatigable <HI>In|du&s;try</HI> and Diligence, that I am legally qualified for the Exerci&s;e of the <HI>Art</HI> I profe&s;s, maugre the inveterate <HI>Malice</HI> of all Op|po&s;ers.</P>
<P><HI>My Lord,</HI> My Life and Con|ver&s;ation, I ble&s;s God, being unattackable, even by Envy it
<PB REF="4">&s;elf, and &s;o being no Reproach to the Name I have the Ho|nour to bear: And your Lord|&s;hip being Celebrated for your <HI>Exemplary</HI> Piety, Charity, and <HI>profound</HI> Knowledge in <HI>Phy&s;ick,</HI> as well as in all other Learned and u&s;eful <HI>Arts</HI> and <HI>Sciences,</HI> and con&s;equently a Proper and <HI>Sufficient</HI> Judge, of the Contents of the following <HI>Treati&s;e.</HI></P>
<P>I have humbly pre&s;um'd to <HI>Dedicate</HI> it to your good Lord|&s;hip, in great Sincerity, but in very plain Language; for if <HI>Nature</HI> had been more kind and liberal to me in <HI>Eloquent</HI> and <HI>Rhetorical</HI> Expre&s;&s;ions, I dur&s;t not have u&s;ed them to your Lord|&s;hip, who takes more Delight in <HI>doing good</HI> to others, than in read|ing <HI>de&s;erved Panegyricks</HI> on your &s;elf.</P>
<PB REF="5">
<P>And therefore if your Lord|&s;hip is pleas'd to <HI>Pardon</HI> or <HI>Excu&s;e</HI> my Confidence in this Addre&s;s, and favourably accept the tender of this diminutive <HI>Tract,</HI> I &s;hall e&s;teem that great Conde&s;cention, as an Eternal Obligation and Honour, con|ferr'd upon,</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED><HI>My good Lord, Your Lord&s;hips Mo&s;t Devoted Humble Servant</HI> John Moore.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
