<HEAD>A PRACTICAL DISCOURSE, Shewing the <HI>Origine, Seat, Symptoms, Cau&s;e,</HI> &amp;c.</HEAD>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Intro|duction in defence of the Au|thor.</NOTE>IF ever any Per&s;on upon the Face of the Univer&s;e, that Dedicated his whole Life to the <HI>doing good,</HI> and rendring him&s;elf <HI>Bene|ficial</HI> to Mankind, has rea&s;on to complain of the Ill and Barbarous u&s;age he has en|countred, from Men of his own <HI>Profe&s;&s;ion,</HI> and others of a <HI>Superior</HI> Station, that pre|tend Authority to <HI>Licen&s;e</HI> or <HI>Suppre&s;s,</HI> all Practioners in the Noble and U&s;eful Arts of <HI>Pharmacy,</HI> and <HI>Admini&s;tring</HI> Phy&s;ick, <HI>I am the Man;</HI> for ever &s;ince I took my leave of the Old and U&s;ele&s;s way of giving Phy|&s;ick, as too many others do, <HI>Blindfold, by Traditional Pre&s;criptions,</HI> and made it my whole
<PB N="8" REF="7">Study and Bu&s;ine&s;s to keep up an entire Corre&s;pondence and Agreement between <HI>Art</HI> and <HI>Nature, Theory</HI> and <HI>Practice;</HI> and made exact and particular Ob&s;ervations in the <HI>difference</HI> of Di&s;ea&s;es, the variety of <HI>Symptoms,</HI> ca&s;ual <HI>Accidents,</HI> and the diver&s;ity of <HI>Con|&s;titutions</HI> in Humane Bodies; and have followed the dictates of a <HI>well-grounded Experi|ence,</HI> in finding out the <HI>E&s;&s;ence</HI> of Di&s;ea&s;es, and the <HI>Efficacy</HI> of Proper Medicines <HI>to Cure them.</HI> The whole Tribe of <HI>common</HI> Practioners, and &s;ome <HI>graduated</HI> Profe&s;&s;ors of Phy&s;ick, that live lazing upon the little Knowledge that comes by <HI>Tradition,</HI> and by &s;tuffing their <HI>Bills,</HI> and <HI>Patients</HI> with Nau&s;eous Re|petitions, of unexperienc'd and con&s;equently <HI>ineffectual</HI> Medicines; have both un&s;uffer|ably calumniated, traduced and &s;lander'd me, with many ridiculous Stories and un|ju&s;t <HI>Cen&s;ures,</HI> as well as loaded me with &s;uch hard and <HI>reproachful</HI> Names, as none but the <HI>bountiful</HI> be&s;towers of them can de&s;erve; &s;o that I am forc'd, to prevent others from being <HI>prejudiced</HI> by fal&s;e Reports and mali|cious In&s;inuations, to take this way of vin|dicating my Reputation, again&s;t the <HI>In&s;ults</HI> of Envious Men, who are as utter Stran|gers to my Per&s;on and Abilities, as them|&s;elves are from the common Principles of <HI>Mode&s;ty, Civility and good Manners.</HI></P>
<P>I could with great facility recriminate upon my Enemies, but I never thought a <HI>Billings-Gate Dialect</HI> any Ornament, or an advantageous Character to a Sober Chri|ftian, which is &s;eldom u&s;ed, but by a bui&s;y &s;ort of <HI>Tatling</HI> Animals, who are out of Humour with every Body, becau&s;e their own ill nature will not &s;uffer 'em to be
<PB N="9" REF="8">pleas'd with them&s;elves. Let <HI>Maevius</HI> and <HI>Bavius</HI> then admire one another, and rail at all the World be&s;ides; I &s;hall for the future be unconcern'd at tho&s;e who are as full of unju&s;t Reproaches, as they are void of good Breeding. I <HI>wi&s;h</HI> to be hated by &s;elf-intere&s;ted <HI>Slanderers</HI> and their Abettors, for the &s;ame rea&s;on for which I <HI>de&s;ire</HI> to be belov'd by all Ingenious, well meaning ho|ne&s;t Men, under all Denominations; as for the re&s;t, I &s;hall &s;ay with the Poet</P>
<Q><L><HI>&V;rg'd by the Ba&s;e, I'm unconcern'd the while,</HI></L>
<L><HI>At lea&s;t regard it with a &s;cornful Smile;</HI></L>
<L><HI>'Twere mean to think of Vengeance on the Vile.</HI></L></Q>
<P>However, &s;ince I know not how far their Hatred, inveterate and implacable <HI>Malice</HI> may extend to my prejudice, among tho&s;e that know not my <HI>veritable</HI> Character, I &s;hall here employ a few Lines to an&s;wer all the Objections they have <HI>rai&s;ed,</HI> and <HI>indu&s;tri|ou&s;ly</HI> &s;catter'd to bla&s;t my Reputation in the Practice of Phy&s;ick, which I have followed with great Succe&s;s for many Years, and which the wor&s;t of my Enemies cannot de|ny, without a&s;&s;urance enough to affirm, that the Sun is not ri&s;en, when to their <HI>&s;hame,</HI> it &s;hines in their Faces from its Illu&s;trious Meridian.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Objections again&s;t the Author.</NOTE>The fir&s;t Quarter in which my profe&s;&s;ed Enemies attack me, is, <HI>That I am but an Apothecary:</HI> 'Tis true, I lay claim to no greater Title, and yet cannot forbear &s;ay|ing, That that Objection is <HI>Ridiculous;</HI> &s;ince being an <HI>Apothecary,</HI> well versd in <HI>Phar|macy,</HI> in the Knowledge of <HI>Drugs,</HI> and the <HI>Compo&s;ition</HI> of Medicines, is, the mo&s;t cer|tain
<PB N="10" REF="9">and regular &s;tep towards the making of a good Phy&s;ician: As has been proved by many Examples in <HI>London</HI> and other Places, where Men that &s;ervd their Times to Apothecaries, and kept Shop many Years, have afterwards took their Degree of <HI>Doctor</HI> in one of our own Univer&s;ities, and pra|cti&s;ed with as great Applau&s;e, and it may be with more <HI>Succe&s;s,</HI> than the re&s;t of their <HI>only</HI> Graduated Brethren. Nor is this method unob&s;erved in other Learned Employments; for many Wi&s;e Men &s;ay, That the way to make an able <HI>Coun&s;ellor,</HI> is, Fir&s;t to educate him as a <HI>Clerk</HI> to an <HI>At|torney.</HI> Having thus blown off this igno|rant and contemptible Objection, I proceed to the Second; which is, <HI>That I never had, an &V;niver&s;ity Education, but am a mere Ignoramus,</HI> as they are pleas'd to Phra&s;e it; But how will they prove their latter Allegation? Did they ever Examine into my Learning and Ability? Do they know my Incapa|city to perform what I undertake? If they did, without doubt I &s;hould long &s;ince have heard of it in <HI>louder</HI> Terms, than by Private Whi&s;pers, Malicious In&s;inuations and Secret Calumnies and A&s;per&s;ions; but &s;uch is their Hatred, that what they dare not aver to my Face, or attempt to prove by <HI>Argument,</HI> they liberally &s;upply by fal&s;e Reports, and forged Clande&s;tine Stories of my In&s;ufficiency, again&s;t a Thou&s;and <HI>credible</HI> Certificates and <HI>Reputable</HI> Te&s;timonies to the contrary; and the&s;e I think &s;ufficient to &s;top the Mouths of <HI>Detraction</HI> and <HI>Envy,</HI> in the Opinion of all good People; and for o|thers, that are <HI>mi&s;lead</HI> by my <HI>Numerous</HI> Ad|ver&s;aries into <HI>uncharitable</HI> Cen&s;ures of me;
<PB N="11" REF="10">let them but con&s;ider, that my Enemies treat me on the &s;core of <HI>Demetrius,</HI> for my &s;afe and &s;hort way of <HI>Practice,</HI> and a great number of Patients dimini&s;hing their <HI>Profit,</HI> they will not wonder that I am con|demn'd in an <HI>Arbitrary</HI> Court, where <HI>Ma|lice is the Pro&s;ecuter, <HI>Intere&s;t</HI> &s;its as Judge, and &s;ordid <HI>Ignorance</HI> is <HI>Fore-Man</HI> of the Jury. I confe&s;s, I have not had the Advantage of an <HI>Academick</HI> Education, but am a &s;incere lover of <HI>Learning,</HI> and de&s;irous of Know|ledge, and tho' I cannot boa&s;t of po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ing much, yet I can a&s;tute all Cen&s;orious <HI>Pedants,</HI> that by conver&s;ing with Learned Men, and a well cho&s;en Library, I take as much pains to <HI>encrea&s;e</HI> my Knowledge, as &s;ome of them do by in&s;ignificant <HI>Diver&s;ions,</HI> and notorious <HI>Debaucheries,</HI> to lo&s;e what they gain'd, if ever they gain'd <HI>any</HI> thing but <HI>Words</HI> at the &V;niver&s;ity.</HI> Be&s;ides, this cavil is wholly <HI>Impertinent,</HI> &s;ince its well known, beyond a po&s;&s;ibility of Contradi|ction, that I am Ma&s;ter of good <HI>Specificks,</HI> and <HI>e&s;tabli&s;h'd</HI> experimented Medicines, of my own <HI>Preparing,</HI> which <HI>Prescribing?</HI> Phy&s;ici|ans cannot pretend to, tho' of the greate&s;t Con&s;equence to Mankind, and who&s;e effi|cacious Vertues I am &s;ure of, and can rely upon, in the mo&s;t <HI>difficult</HI> plunging Ca&s;es in re&s;pect of Safety, and generally with Suc|ce&s;s; and all this confirmed by numerous Te&s;timonies of <HI>Cured</HI> Patients, which I am of Opinion, is all that ought t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> be required of a <HI>good</HI> Phy&s;ician; and yet for want of the empty Title of <HI>Doctor,</HI> and a <HI>Coach</HI> and Equipage, I mu&s;t, it &s;eems, be called <HI>Quack</HI> and <HI>Emperick,</HI> by cho&s;e <HI>Doni</HI> of the Pro|fe&s;&s;ion, who have not much more Skill in
<PB N="12" REF="11">the true Practice of Phy&s;ick, which I take to be the <HI>Cure of Di&s;ea&s;es,</HI> than what they collect from the old exploded <HI>Methodus Medendi,</HI> which when the World grows Wi&s;er, will vani&s;h into its original <HI>nothing,</HI> and give place <HI>to</HI> &s;olid, certain and veri|table <HI>Experience</HI> in the Cure of Di&s;ea&s;es.</P>
<P>And that I may contribute to this great <HI>End,</HI> of advancing <HI>u&s;eful</HI> Knowledge in Phy|&s;ick, and that my Enemies may not think I am reduced to a <HI>perpetual</HI> &s;ilence in my own ju&s;t Defence, by their vain <HI>Threatnings</HI> and <HI>injurious</HI> Mi&s;repre&s;entations of my Per&s;on and Capacity for the Practice of Phy&s;ick, I have taken up a re&s;olution to Print &s;e|veral <HI>Di&s;cour&s;es</HI> upon <HI>tho&s;e</HI> Di&s;ea&s;es, that God has ble&s;s'd me with the Knowledge of, and given me wonderful &s;ucce&s;s in their Cures, that have frequently baffled the Endeavours of many Eminent <HI>Profe&s;&s;ors:</HI> And &s;hall be|gin with a Treati&s;e upon the CHOLICK.</P>
<P>Now in di&s;cour&s;ing this Subject, to avoid all unnece&s;&s;ary and over Nice and Curious Di&s;tinction, and Definitions, that rather puzzle Men's Intellects, than benefit their Understandings, I &s;hall under the general Name, vulgarly called <HI>Cholick,</HI> treat of it as an Accidental and Particular Di&s;temper, ari&s;ing from an evident Cau&s;e alone, and without a previous di&s;po&s;ition in any Per|&s;on indifferently; for &s;o, alterations in the <HI>Sex No<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">naturalia</HI> often rai&s;e great commotions in the <HI>Vi&s;cera</HI> of the Belly with extremity of Pain: After that, I &s;hall con&s;ider this Di&s;ea&s;e in its <HI>Procartick</HI> or <HI>pre-exi&s;tent</HI> Cau&s;e, as co-operating with others that are &s;ub|&s;equent, which will nece&s;&s;arily lead me to
<PB N="13" REF="12">particular Di&s;cour&s;es upon the various kinds, and the &s;everal Species of this Di&s;temper under the denominations of the Cholick in the <HI>Stomach;</HI> the <HI>Hy&s;terick</HI> Cholick, the <HI>Scor|butick</HI> Cholick; the <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> the <HI>Caeliack</HI> Cholick, a <HI>Diarrhea,</HI> a <HI>Lientary,</HI> a <HI>Dy&s;entry,</HI> &amp;c. All which Di&s;tempers I &s;hall treat particularly, and to avoid Confu&s;ion and over burthening the Memory, under every Head I &s;hall &s;hew the <HI>Origine Seminium</HI> or <HI>Minera</HI> of each Di&s;ea&s;e; what part of the Body is <HI>primarily</HI> affected; then proceed to the <HI>Symptoms</HI> and Method of <HI>Cure,</HI> and con|clude with &s;ome Ob&s;ervations and Exam|ples, wherein my own Medicines have been wonderfully &s;ucce&s;sful; which I always keep ready prepared by me, to di&s;po&s;e of, to all that think fit to come or &s;end for them.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The E&s;&s;ence or Nature of the Cho|lick.</NOTE>The Cholick called in <HI>Greek</HI> <GAP DESC="foreign">, in <HI>Latin Collica Pa&s;&s;io,</HI> becau&s;e by &s;ome Phy&s;itians, 'tis &s;uppo&s;ed, tho' fal&s;ly, to have its &s;eat wholly in &s;ome part or other of the Se|cond of the great Guts, called <HI>Colon;</HI> is a Vellication or &s;evere Griping, Twitching, Gnawing Pain in certain Parts of the <HI>Ab|domen,</HI> which commonly produce Vomit|ings, Cramps and Contractions, almo&s;t of all the <HI>Vi&s;cera</HI> of the Belly: Sometimes the Navel and its Neighbouring Parts are drawn inward, accompanied with Pains as if they were boared with a Gimlet: Sometimes they &s;well, being blown up with the exce&s;s of Wind: The <HI>Inte&s;tines</HI> by an inverted Motion of the <HI>Fibres</HI> are often drawn up|wards, in&s;omuch that the Belly being ex|treamly bound, di&s;charges little or nothing at all; nay, tho' it be frequently provoked to do it by Gly&s;ters and Suppo&s;itories, yet
<PB N="14" REF="13">it does not ea&s;ily throw out its Con|tents.</P>
<P>That the Stomach is likewi&s;e convul&s;ed with the <HI>Duodenum</HI> and Gall Bladder, mani|fe&s;tly appears from the plentiful vomiting of Yellow or Green Choler. Sometimes the <HI>&V;reters</HI> and the Bladder which contains the Urine, are &s;o contracted, that during the whole Fit, the Urine is either &s;topt, or voided more &s;paringly: Be&s;ides, the Head is grieved with <HI>Vertiginous</HI> effects, either preceding or following the inva&s;ion of this Di&s;ea&s;e, and if the Cholick encrea&s;es and becomes <HI>Inveterate,</HI> it often cau&s;es Pain in the outward Members and terminates in a <HI>Pal&s;ey.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Its direful Effects.</NOTE>Nay, the Sick commonly endures all kinds of Pains; one while <HI>burning</HI> with intole|rable <HI>Heat,</HI> another time <HI>chill'd</HI> with extream <HI>Cold;</HI> &s;ometimes it &s;eems to be fix'd and as it were piercing the <HI>Loins,</HI> or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ther whiles <HI>pricking</HI> with <HI>wandring</HI> repeated <HI>Thru&s;ts;</HI> anon <HI>di&s;tending</HI> or <HI>beating</HI> the Loins, or only <HI>pre&s;&s;ing</HI> them with the <HI>&s;en&s;e of weight,</HI> or <HI>burning, corroding, rending</HI> Pain; or is troubled either with a <HI>continual</HI> or <HI>interrupted Pul&s;ation,</HI> and afterward returning again, or wonder|fully <HI>writhing</HI> and <HI>contorting</HI> any other way, &s;carce to be expre&s;&s;ed by the Patient, or explain'd by the Phy&s;ician.</P>
<P>Now tho' all the differences occurring in this Di&s;temper with its <HI>Original</HI> are very difficult to be a&s;&s;ign'd, numbred, or re|duced into a certain Order, and much more to make an exact Examination of all the <HI>Symptoms</HI> and <HI>Cau&s;es,</HI> and thence to give a &s;ollid judgment of every one; yet I &s;hall attempt it, by exhibiting them from the
<PB N="15" REF="14">be&s;t Authorities, and leave the choice to your own Election, as they are mo&s;t agree|able to your Rea&s;on and <HI>Experience,</HI> which is the Mi&s;tre&s;s both of the Learned and Unskilful.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Origin of the Cho|lick.</NOTE>Some are of Opinion that the <HI>Origine</HI> of this Di&s;ea&s;e, proceeds from the efferve&s;cency of vicious Blood; others from an Ob&s;truction of the <HI>Capillary</HI> Veins of the Stomach and Guts, by which the <HI>Blood</HI> is forced to &s;tand &s;till in the <HI>Ve&s;&s;els,</HI> till at length after a great <HI>Di&s;tention</HI> the Ve&s;&s;els bur&s;t and the Blood is effu&s;&s;ed, which breeds a &s;en&s;ible Inflamation and violent Pul&s;ation about the Part affected. Others &s;ay it ari&s;es from an over <HI>vi&s;cous Phlegm</HI> mix'd with <HI>Choler,</HI> of|fen&s;ive both in its Salti&s;h <HI>Acrimony</HI> and Vo|latile <HI>Oiline&s;s,</HI> by which the <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> Phlegm is rarified into <HI>Wind,</HI> and if the Excrements are contain'd beyond their due time, they harden and &s;tick to the Gut, by which the natural <HI>Ferment</HI> is viciated, and the Windy Gu&s;ts are more rarified, and being &s;hut up in the <HI>Cavity</HI> of the Gut <HI>Colon</HI> it cau&s;es a violent di&s;ten&s;ion and contraction of it.</P>
<P>Some again impute it the di&s;orders and Convul&s;ions of the <HI>Nerves</HI> running from the Me&s;enterick <HI>Plexus,</HI> which vicious hu|mours as afore&s;aid, lodg'd in the <HI>Inte&s;tines,</HI> and tho&s;e by a Forreign <HI>irritation</HI> of their <HI>Nerves,</HI> equally attended by the &s;ucce&s;&s;ive returns of <HI>Cold,</HI> and <HI>Heat,</HI> cau&s;e tearing, wringing and c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="6 letters">cting Pains.</P>
<P>Others a&s;cribe <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">s Original to the a|bounding Acidity and Acrimony of the <HI>Pancreatick juice,</HI> occa&s;ion'd by over &s;harp Food; eating raw Fruits, by Summer <HI>Air</HI> too Hot, by Winter Air too <HI>Cold,</HI> or at lea&s;t
<PB N="16" REF="15">too <HI>Sharp;</HI> by <HI>Fear, Sorrow, extream Grief or Solicitude of Mind;</HI> by continued <HI>Watchings</HI> which con&s;ume the <HI>Animal</HI> Spirits, and by con&s;equence encrea&s;ing the Acrimony of any Humours, produce <HI>Hypocondriack &s;uffocations,</HI> and al&s;o Pains, &s;everely racking and con|torting the <HI>Guts.</HI> Now the Rea&s;ons why I cannot agree with many Phy&s;icians, that Cholick Pains proceed from the &s;harp and irritative contents of the <HI>Colon,</HI> is, becau&s;e tho&s;e Medicines which loo&s;en the Belly, and copious&s;ly expel <HI>Featus</HI>'s and the <HI>Faeces,</HI> would undoubtedly give mo&s;t certain Re|lief, the contrary of which too often hap|pens, <HI>viz.</HI> That after frequent or violent Purging, that Di&s;ea&s;e becomes wor&s;e. Nor can I agree with the Notion, that Cholick Pains proceed only from the <HI>Pancreatick juice</HI> mix'd with <HI>Choler,</HI> becau&s;e it's impo&s;&s;ible, according to <HI>Sylvius de la Boe</HI> that the Juice of the <HI>Pancreas in any manner or degree &s;owre,</HI> &s;hould mix with <HI>Choler,</HI> abounding with a <HI>bitter</HI> and <HI>volatile</HI> Salt. Therefore,</P>
<P>I firmly adhere to the Opinion of the Learned Dr. <HI>Willis,</HI> who with great rea&s;on, places the Origine of this Di&s;ea&s;e among the effects of the <HI>Brain</HI> and the <HI>Genus Nervo&s;um,</HI> alledging, that certain <HI>Recrements</HI> of the <HI>Nervous</HI> Humour, falling from the Brain by the <HI>Nerves,</HI> and pa&s;&s;ing thence into the <HI>Me|&s;entry</HI> and other <HI>Foldings</HI> of the <HI>Abdomen,</HI> are there ama&s;s'd and heaped together, which if they are &s;o gro&s;s, thick and <HI>vi&s;cous,</HI> that they cannot be received and &s;ent away by the <HI>Lymphaducts,</HI> or di&s;till'd out into the Cavities of the <HI>Inte&s;tines,</HI> by the &s;mall Branches of the Ve&s;&s;els, then <HI>Stagnating</HI> and being heaped together by degrees into tho&s;e
<PB N="17" REF="16">Parts, they ari&s;e at length to an <HI>irritative</HI> plenitude: And afterward that Matter becoming more degenerate, and more offen|&s;ive by <HI>Stagnation,</HI> and growing turged on &s;ome occa&s;ion; or of its own accord or el&s;e fermenting with the <HI>Salino-fix'd Humour,</HI> &s;ent thither from the <HI>Blood,</HI> will torture the Patient with very trouble&s;ome and painful <HI>Corrugations</HI> in the Branches of the <HI>Nerves</HI> and Nervous <HI>Fibres,</HI> with which the <HI>Me&s;en|tery</HI> is innumerably furni&s;h'd: Which ef|fects of them, do &s;eldom or never cea&s;e till the <HI>fermenting Matter</HI> is either di&s;cu&s;s'd, or <HI>expre&s;s'd</HI> into the Cavities of the Inte&s;tines, or at length by Care and the Application of proper Medicines, they are utterly &s;ub|dued.</P>
<P>Having thus briefly &s;hew'd you the <HI>Na|ture</HI> of the <HI>Cholick</HI> in the direful effects it produces, together with its Origination, I &s;hall, according to promi&s;e, proceed to the <HI>Place</HI> that is primarily affected in Human Bodies.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The &s;eat of the Cholick</NOTE><HI>Senertus</HI> and <HI>Riverius,</HI> place it in the up|per Orifice of the <HI>Stomach,</HI> which is of ex|qui&s;ite Sen&s;e, by rea&s;on of the intermixture of <HI>Nerves,</HI> with which it is &s;tored from the <HI>vaga &s;exta,</HI> from whence Branches being communicated to the <HI>Heart</HI> that noble Part is al&s;o affected by Con&s;ent, and di&s;per&s;es the Pain into almo&s;t every part Internal and external.</P>
<P>Dr. <HI>Blankard,</HI> Profe&s;&s;or of Phy&s;ick, at <HI>Middleburgh,</HI> in <HI>Zealand,</HI> &s;ays, The Cholick is a vehement Pain, proceeding from an ill di&s;po&s;ition of the <HI>Animal Spirits,</HI> &s;eated in the <HI>Abdomen,</HI> but begins in the <HI>Nervous Plexus</HI>'s or <HI>Foldings</HI> of the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> and is
<PB N="18" REF="17">by &s;ome Men fal&s;ly imputed to have its re&s;idence in the Gut <HI>Colon.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Michael Etmuller,</HI> late Profe&s;&s;or of Phy&s;ick in the Univer&s;ity of <HI>Leipt&s;ick,</HI> &s;ays, Cholick Pains and Gripings in the great Guts, are chiefly felt in the <HI>Colon,</HI> e&s;pecially in that part of it towards the circumference of the Belly, upon the Left-&s;ide, where 'tis &s;trait|ned and incurvated, and con&s;equently more liable to the bla&s;t and &s;hocks of Wind, and more apt to &s;top the Circulation of the Excrements, and cau&s;e their Swelling up in|to a hard or &s;oft <HI>Tumor.</HI> This Pain and Tumor is frequently imputed to the <HI>Spleen,</HI> but erroneou&s;ly; for the <HI>Colon,</HI> &s;ays he, is its u&s;ual and proper Seat; and &s;ometimes it veers about to the Right-&s;ide of the Belly, upon the outermo&s;t Circumference, where the &s;ame <HI>Colon</HI> pur&s;ues its Cour&s;e.</P>
<P>Sometimes the&s;e Pains reach only the Small Guts, and then their Station is about the <HI>Navel</HI> and Centre of the Belly, and are much more violent than tho&s;e in the Great Guts; if they range not beyond the <HI>Duodenum,</HI> or the beginning of the <HI>Jejunum,</HI> they are felt in the <HI>Loins,</HI> and are often mi|&s;taken for <HI>Nephritick</HI> Pains, or tho&s;e cau&s;ed by the Convul&s;ion of the <HI>Me&s;enterick</HI> Nerves, or Tumors, or Ulcers in the <HI>Pancreas.</HI> I dare not &s;ay any of the&s;e Opinions are He|terodox, becau&s;e &s;ometime or other Pains do po&s;&s;e&s;s all the Parts above mention'd.</P>
<P>However, for very good Rea&s;ons grounded upon many Experiments in Anatomy, I ad|here chiefly to Doctor <HI>Willis,</HI> who &s;ays, The Part in Human Bodies <HI>primarily</HI> affected in the Cholick, is the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> and its Ner|vous <HI>Foldings</HI> under the Navel, which cau&s;es
<PB N="19" REF="18">cruel Pain, as if a Stake was &s;tuck there, or a Piercer were making a Hole: Be&s;ides, round about, almo&s;t in the whole <HI>Abdomen,</HI> by rea&s;on of the <HI>Inte&s;tines</HI> being <HI>variou&s;ly</HI> drawn forward and backward, at the &s;ame time in different Places, wandring Pains &s;hoot this way and that way; and the mo|tion of the <HI>Fibres</HI> being di&s;compo&s;ed or in|verted, as well in tho&s;e Parts as in the <HI>pri|mary</HI> Ve&s;&s;els, the Belly is in a manner al|ways bound, and there follows &s;ometimes a &s;upper&s;&s;ion of Urine, or very little is made. Be&s;ides, the <HI>Duodenum</HI> the Gall Bladder with its Channels and the bottom of the Stomach being affected with a <HI>Cramp,</HI> and their <HI>Fibres</HI> being drawn upward, a frequent Vomiting with a copious ca&s;ting up Matter of Yellow or Greeni&s;h colour often happens during the Fit.</P>
<P>In a Fit of the Cholick, al&s;o be&s;ides Pains of the Belly, there are likewi&s;e violent Pains of the <HI>Loins,</HI> raging in the 1ower parts of the <HI>Back,</HI> which certainly cannot pro|ceed from the <HI>irritation of any Inte&s;tine;</HI> but its ea&s;y to conceive they may ari&s;e from a <HI>Morbific</HI> Cau&s;e lodg'd in the <HI>Me&s;entery:</HI> For ina&s;much as &s;everal con&s;iderable <HI>Nerves</HI> of the Loins enter into the great <HI>Nervous fold|ing</HI> of the <HI>Me&s;entery;</HI> &s;o from hence, not on|ly painful Convul&s;ions are conveyed by <HI>con|&s;ent</HI> from one Part to another; but its al&s;o probable, that certain <HI>Recrements</HI> of the Back likewi&s;e, and of the Loins, are derived into the <HI>Me&s;entery</HI> by this Pa&s;&s;age, and that in &s;ome &s;ort, for this rea&s;on, <HI>Scorbutical</HI> Per&s;ons are &s;o very obnoxious to Gripes of the Belly, and Loo&s;ene&s;s that attends it, which confirms me in the Opinion that the Nervous <HI>Flexus</HI>
<PB N="20" REF="19">of the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> is the fir&s;t Part affected with the <HI>Cholick,</HI> and that its &s;eat is not in the <HI>Cavities</HI> or <HI>T<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">nicles</HI> of the Inte&s;tines, nor the Morbifick Matter conveyed by the <HI>Arteries,</HI> but by <HI>Nerves.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Diagno|&s;tick Sym|ptoms.</NOTE><HI>Diagno&s;tick</HI> Signs of the Cholick, are, very &s;harp Pains, &s;ometimes moveable and other whiles fix'd to a certain place; &s;ome|times the Pain is in the region of the <HI>Stomach</HI> or in the <HI>Reins,</HI> &s;ometimes <HI>above</HI> and &s;ome|times <HI>below</HI> the Navel, &s;o that by the com|pari&s;on of other Signs, you mu&s;t di&s;tingui&s;h between the <HI>Cholick</HI> and Pains of the <HI>Stone</HI> or <HI>Spleen,</HI> which are frequently mi&s;taken one for the other, even by Phy&s;icians them|&s;elves.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Progno|&s;tick Sym|ptoms of the Cholick.</NOTE><HI>Progno&s;ticks</HI> of the Cholick, are vulgarly enough known, that is to &s;ay, an <HI>Accidental</HI> Cholick ri&s;ing from an <HI>evident</HI> cau&s;e alone, is commonly &s;afe, and admits of an ea&s;y Cure; but an <HI>habitual</HI> one, is not eradicated but with great Difficulty, as to its di&s;po|&s;ition, &s;o that the Fits may return no more; for &s;ometimes the <HI>Fits</HI> them&s;elves, notwith|&s;tanding the Application of Medicines, are very <HI>ob&s;tinate</HI> and continue many Days, nay, Weeks and Months, and &s;ometimes are never cured but by Death. Thus much for &s;igns; But &s;ince I have branch'd out this Di&s;ea&s;e into &s;everal Parts, I &s;hall take leave, once for all, to &s;hew, how you may di&s;tin|gui&s;h one Di&s;ea&s;e from another by the Urine.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Signs by the Urine.</NOTE>If the Urine is <HI>Watery,</HI> 'tis a <HI>Nephritick</HI> Cholick, if highly tinctur'd towards the middle, and colour'd on the Surface, and the <HI>Anus</HI> is ob&s;tinately bound; 'tis a <HI>Scor|butick</HI> Cholick; if <HI>Re&s;piration</HI> is difficult and
<PB N="21" REF="20">the <HI>Brea&s;t</HI> afflicted, 'tis a <HI>Hy&s;terick</HI> Cholick; if the <HI>Convul&s;ion</HI> of the <HI>Inte&s;tines</HI> is accom|panied with Pain extending to the <HI>Pubes</HI> and <HI>Haunch-Bone,</HI> the <HI>Womb</HI> is di&s;order'd; if the Urine is clear and of a reddi&s;h <HI>Yellow,</HI> 'tis a <HI>Cholerick</HI> Cholick, if the Pain is tearing and the Urine <HI>Milky</HI> and Pale, impregnated with a large <HI>Sediment,</HI> the <HI>Me&s;enterick Nerves</HI> are affected.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of the com|mon Cho|lick.</NOTE>The <HI>Antecedent</HI> Cau&s;es of the <HI>Common</HI> Cho|lick, which I only treat of under this Head, are, the Di&s;order and Convul&s;ions of the <HI>Nerves</HI> running from the great <HI>Me&s;enterick Plexus,</HI> which cau&s;e tearing, wringing and contracting Pains: Sometimes occa&s;ion'd by <HI>Nephritick</HI> Pains and <HI>Child-Birth,</HI> when the <HI>Me&s;enterick</HI> folding, being irritated, by its concour&s;e with the Nerves of the <HI>Kidneys</HI> and the <HI>Womb,</HI><NOTE PLACE="marg">Antece|dent Cau-Cau&s;es.</NOTE> pulls and contracts both the <HI>Stomach</HI> and <HI>Guts</HI> which it &s;upplies with Nerves. At other times they are re|tainers to &s;ome fix'd, permanent, <HI>habitual</HI> Cau&s;e, which tho' it lye hid for &s;ome time, has always an A&s;cendant in the Body. The&s;e are either <HI>Hypochondriack, Hy&s;terick</HI> or <HI>Scor|butick,</HI> as I &s;hall further &s;hew, when I treat particularly of tho&s;e Di&s;ea&s;es a part, and are owing to the Convul&s;ion of the <HI>Me&s;en|terick Plexus,</HI> to which the Inte&s;tines are an|nex'd, being gall'd with a peccant Acid.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Procatar|tick Cau&s;es.</NOTE>The <HI>Procatartick,</HI> or Pre-exi&s;tent Cau&s;e of this Di&s;ea&s;e which co-operates with others that are &s;ub&s;equent, are two fold; Fir&s;t, That many <HI>Recrements</HI> or &s;uperfluous things are heaped together in the Nervous Li|quor; and Secondly, That they being ad|mitted chiefly into the Nerves of the Vi&s;cera of the Belly, and &s;o conveyed into the <HI>Me|&s;entery,</HI>
<PB N="22" REF="21">there create the Morbid Minera's of this Di&s;temper; for the former of the&s;e generally happening by the Di&s;temper of the Brain, by admitting <HI>Heterogeneous Particles</HI> with the Nervous Juice into its cu&s;tody, the whole <HI>Animal</HI> Oeconomy is &s;o di&s;turb'd, that it cannot evacuate the common &s;uper|fluities by its ordinary Conveyance; and this cau&s;es the incongruous Matter that can|not be &s;ent from the Brain, to force its pa&s;|&s;age into the Nerves of the <HI>Par vagum,</HI> which are open and ready to receive it. Se|condly, That this &s;uperfluous Matter run|ning in this manner into the <HI>Par vagum</HI> of the Nerves, is depo&s;ed in the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> or other foldings within the Abdomen, and nece&s;&s;arily makes the Morbid &s;eat in the <HI>Me&s;entery.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Evident Cau&s;es.</NOTE>The <HI>evident</HI> Cau&s;es of the Cholick are al&s;o of two &s;orts; Fir&s;t, Such as being injurious to the Brain and <HI>Genus Nervo&s;um,</HI> cau&s;e the Morbifick Matter to &s;uper abound: Or, Secondly by agitating the Blood and Hu|mors, &s;tir up the conglobated Ma&s;s to Pain, cau&s;ing more fervent and &s;udden efferve|&s;cencies. And here &s;ome will imagine I &s;hould proceed to di&s;cour&s;e the many and diver&s;i|fied occa&s;ions, by which the Pains of the Cholick are caus'd in Per&s;ons pre-di&s;po&s;ed to them; but that would be nau&s;eating the Reader with <HI>Cramben bi&s;coctum,</HI> having &s;uf|ficiently done it already, in the Paragraph ent<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">tuled the direful effects of the Cholick, Page <HI>the</HI> 14th.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cure of the Ch<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">lick.</NOTE>And now according to the Method I have pre&s;cribed to my &s;elf, I am brought to treat of what ought to be the Main and Principal de&s;ign of every <HI>Practitioner</HI> in Phy&s;ick in
<PB N="23" REF="22">all Di&s;ea&s;es, <HI>viz. The Cure of the Di&s;ea&s;e.</HI> To compa&s;s which great end, Three primary In|dications are &s;ugge&s;ted. Fir&s;t, To appea&s;e the <HI>Pains</HI> in the Fit. Secondly, To take a|way the <HI>Cau&s;e</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;e that the Fits may no more, or not &s;o frequently return. Thirdly, To re-invigorate the Patient's <HI>Strength,</HI> and fortify his Con&s;titution, in order to the Comfortable enjoyment of Life.</P>
<P>To appea&s;e the torturing Pains in the Paroxi&s;m, Lenifying and Emollient Gly&s;ters only, ought to be frequently injected into the Body, that the Corrugations of the <HI>Fi|bres</HI> may be mitigated, and the raging of the <HI>Spirits</HI> appea&s;ed. To this end, <HI>Warm Milk with Sugar, or rather Molo&s;&s;us, or Syrup of Violets: Al&s;o Emollient Decoctions of March-Mallows, Herb Mercury, and the Flowers of Melilot with Oil of Almonds; al&s;o a &s;trong Decoction of a Sheep's-Head with the Wool on it, or Calves-Feet, are proper to be u&s;ed:</HI> Sometimes a Gly&s;ter of <HI>mear Oil of Olives or of Lin&s;eeds,</HI> have given Ea&s;e, when others have failed. But if this &s;ort of Gly&s;ters are ineffectual and do not come away, or an&s;wer their end &s;tronger mu&s;t be u&s;ed, to force the Humours from the little Mouths of the <HI>Arteries.</HI> For this purpo&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">et Carminative or bitter Decoctions be prep<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">red, in which di&s;&s;olve <HI>Electuary Dia|phoenic<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">, Diacatholicon, or e Baccis Lauri, or Species Hierae,</HI> to which Liquors its cu&s;tomary to add, Two or Three Ounces of the infu&s;ion of <HI>Crocus Mettalorum:</HI> Or to a Pound of an <HI>Emollient Decoction,</HI> add of <HI>Venice Turpentine di&s;&s;olv'd with the Yolk of an Egg, one Ounce;</HI> or take the <HI>&V;rine</HI> of a Healthy Man, <HI>Venice Turpentine di&s;&s;olv'd, one Ounce and half, and
<PB N="24" REF="23">with one Ounce of Molo&s;&s;us mix'd with the re&s;t, make a Gly&s;ter.</HI> The <HI>Bal&s;amick</HI> Particles of the <HI>Turpentine</HI> diffu&s;ed every where, are de|&s;ign'd to remove the Morbifick or <HI>Stagnating</HI> Matter, or encline that which is <HI>Acetous,</HI> or otherwi&s;e degenerate, to a better Tem|perament.</P>
<P>If the Inte&s;tines are much contracted by <HI>vicious</HI> Matter lodg'd within them, <HI>Purgations</HI> ought to be prohibited, for fear they <HI>promo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">e</HI> the Contraction, and <HI>lock up</HI> the Excrements clo&s;er. If this Ca&s;e happens in your Practice, <HI>Whey,</HI> or an Ounce of the <HI>Oil of Almonds, with Canary Wind and Sperma Caeti,</HI> are more effectual than the &s;tronge&s;t <HI>Catharticks,</HI> If the Cholick is attended with a Tenacious <HI>vi&s;cid Humour,</HI> and a heavy boring Pain, Purgatives mix'd with <HI>attenuating</HI> Specificks are allowable; tho' I have ob&s;erv'd, 'tis bet|ter to do &s;o after the Fit has made &s;ome progre&s;s, and the Symptoms are a little <HI>mit|tigated,</HI> than ju&s;t in the beginning, e&s;pecially if the Pain is violent; but take notice, that if the Guts are <HI>inflamed,</HI> all <HI>Laxatives</HI> of what|&s;oever <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ind are extreamly pernicious; for a fierc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">nd very violent Cholick, if it pro|ceed from an <HI>Inflamation</HI> or <HI>Ab&s;ce&s;s</HI> of &s;ome of the Inte&s;tines, generally u&s;hers in a Mor|tal <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">External Applica|tions.</NOTE>As for <HI>External</HI> Applications again&s;t Cho|licks, let the Belly and Navel be well fo|mented with <HI>Liniments,</HI> of expre&s;s'd <HI>Oils,</HI> mix'd with tho&s;e that are <HI>Di&s;till'd. Galbanum</HI> melted and mix'd with the Di&s;till'd Oils of <HI>Spike and Amber.</HI> Plaifters made of <HI>Tachamahas, Bal&s;am of Peru, or that of Bay-Berries,</HI> with that of <HI>Tobacco;</HI> Catapla&s;ms of <HI>Hor&s;e-Dung,</HI> with Oil of <HI>Rue;</HI> and quilted Bags of <HI>Mil|let-&s;eeds,</HI>
<PB N="25" REF="24">or of <HI>Anodyn</HI> and <HI>Aromatic</HI> Ingre|tlients; are like wi&s;e apply'd to the Belly with good &s;ucce&s;s. But if the Gripes of the Belly do not remit by the u&s;e of the&s;e things, you mu&s;t have recour&s;e to <HI>Hypnoticks,</HI> which being given in a &s;itting Do&s;e, often gives Relief. And in <HI>continued</HI> Cholicks notwith|&s;tanding &s;ome Men, Who&s;e <HI>Ignorance,</HI> is as con&s;iderable as their <HI>In&s;olence,</HI> loudly cla|mour again&s;t the u&s;e of <HI>Mercurial</HI> Medi|cines, yet the rai&s;ing a gentle <HI>Salivation</HI> when the Morbifick Matter is plentifully gather'd together in the <HI>Nervous Plexus's,</HI> and other places about the <HI>Abdomen,</HI> and there &s;ticking fa&s;t, &s;o as not to be moved by other Medicines, <HI>Calomel</HI> may be given to the Relief of the Patient, and without Reproach to the Phy&s;ician.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Pre|&s;ervative Indication.</NOTE>To refre&s;h the Strength and falling Spi|rits of the Sick, and to order yet a greater Apparatus again&s;t the Di&s;ea&s;e, give <HI>Liquid Laudanum tartariz'd, at Bed-time, in a Spoon|ful of the Water of Camomil Flowers,</HI> drinking after it, of the &s;ame &s;ix Spoonfuls, and let it be repeated every other, or every third Night. And whil&s;t you are u&s;ing the&s;e Me|dicines for appea&s;ing Pains, let Purging Re|medies have their due Turns, to de&s;troy the <HI>Seminium</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;e, and to prevent its return, <HI>Vomiting</HI> and <HI>Purging,</HI> and in a <HI>Hot</HI> Temperament <HI>Ph<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ebotomy</HI> ought to be u&s;ed: And in&s;tead of <HI>Baths</HI> and <HI>Sudorificks, Diure|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">icks</HI> may be more advantageou&s;ly given.</P>
<P>And where the Cholick is of long continu|ance and ob&s;tinate, <HI>Spaw-Water</HI> coming from <HI>Iron-Mines,</HI> are often u&s;ed with good Succe&s;s:</P>
<PB N="26" REF="25">
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Vital Indication.</NOTE>Next, The <HI>Vital</HI> Indication ought to be join'd with the <HI>Curatory,</HI> and to be now and then <HI>interchangeably</HI> u&s;ed with it: To that end, let Remedies be u&s;ed which &s;upport the Patient's <HI>Strength,</HI> refre&s;h his <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">pirits</HI> and procure certain times of <HI>Truce</HI> again&s;t the Fits of the Di&s;ea&s;e. Let the Di&s;ea&s;ed be du&s;y &s;upplied with <HI>Cordials, Paregoricks</HI> and <HI>Hypnoticks,</HI> which in the <HI>Cholick</HI> are &s;o ab&s;o|lutely nece&s;&s;ary, that the Patient <HI>cannot live</HI> without them, nor the Phy&s;ician <HI>ju&s;tif</HI> him|&s;elf, before the Tribunal of his own Con|&s;cience. In Con&s;titutions that are not <HI>Hot, Spirits of Heart-Horn, of Soot, of Sal-Armoni|ack &s;uccinated, al&s;o Tincture of Antimony, or o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Coral,</HI> are all very commendable. And when the Sick is deliver'd from his <HI>Pains,</HI> and has recover'd a <HI>competency</HI> of Strength; to com|pleat his Cure, I recommend travelling <HI>long</HI> Journies on Hor&s;eback, or in a Coach, for &s;uch <HI>excitations</HI> of the Parts, will <HI>&s;trengthen</HI> the Bowels, <HI>&s;hake</HI> off the Relicks of the Di&s;|ea&s;e, and make Life Plea&s;ant and Comfort|able, till the devouring Teeth of Time &s;hall de&s;troy that as well as every thing el&s;e.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Au|thor's own Remedies.</NOTE>Having thus briefly given you the <HI>Nature, Origine, Seat, Symptoms, Cau&s;e</HI> and <HI>Cure</HI> of this Excru&s;iating Di&s;ea&s;e call'd the Cholick, with the <HI>choice&s;t</HI> Remedies u&s;ed by the mo&s;t celebrated Phy&s;icians of former Ages, and the pre&s;ent Time; I &s;hall now, according to Promi&s;e, &s;ay &s;omething of my own Me|dicines, that the bountiful <HI>Giver of all good things</HI> has ble&s;s d me with the Knowledge of, and which I can depend upon, from uncon|tradicted <HI>Experience</HI> in many Years Practice, for the certain <HI>Cure</HI> of this Di&s;ea&s;e, in all <HI>Cureable</HI> Ca&s;es, and for giving <HI>Ea&s;e</HI> in the mo&s;t
<PB N="27" REF="26"><HI>Dangerous,</HI> who&s;e Ob&s;tinacy and Inveteracy will not admit, of a <HI>Perfect</HI> Cure: Which Remedies are of three, &s;orts, a <HI>Chimical Elixir,</HI> an <HI>Anticholical Cordial Water, Pills, and an Electuary;</HI> all &s;afe and Salubrious in their <HI>Nature,</HI> and effectual in their <HI>Operations,</HI> as will be atte&s;ted by <HI>numerous</HI> Patients that have committed them&s;elves to my <HI>Care,</HI> and found extraordinary <HI>Benefit</HI> by them; when Men of greater <HI>Names,</HI> after long <HI>Tryals</HI> have been un&s;ucce&s;sful, to the infinite <HI>Trouble</HI> and great <HI>Expence</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;ed; both which will be prevented by the Method I take, in a happy conjunction of <HI>Speculative</HI> and <HI>Experimental</HI> Knowledge, as the only remedy of the Inconveniencies that cramp a Suc|ce&s;sful Practice.</P>
<P>The Medicines I exhibit are <HI>&s;ure,</HI> and the Knowledge I have of their <HI>vertue,</HI> is not the effect of my <HI>Rea&s;oning;</HI> but of my <HI>Ob&s;erva|tion,</HI> &s;o that tho&s;e that u&s;e them will find them Succe&s;sful. I &s;ay, this Knowledge is not the Fruits of my <HI>Rea&s;on,</HI> becau&s;e in reality it is not; and further, to &s;et this A&s;&s;ertion right, it cannot be &s;o; for in the matter of <HI>Medicines,</HI> we have no other way to follow, but that of Ob&s;ervation: For to offer to di&s;cover, by Rea&s;on alone, the <HI>vertue</HI> of Medicaments, is the way never to find what we &s;eek for I theref re apply my &s;elf to <HI>Experience,</HI> and leave tho&s;e Tricks and vain Subtilities, which according to <HI>Quintilian,</HI> render us like tho&s;e little <HI>In&s;ects,</HI> that are never pleas'd but when they are among Thorns and Briars. Its high time to &s;hake off this School Phy&s;ick, which is good for nothing but <HI>wrangling,</HI> and attain a <HI>po&s;itive Phy&s;ick,</HI> which is of u&s;e in Practice. By po|&s;itive
<PB N="28" REF="27">Phy&s;ick, I don't mean one made up of <HI>Authorities,</HI> which con&s;i&s;ts in knowing the Sentiments of divers Authors upon a con|troverted Point, as in Po&s;itive Divinity: But I mean one that con&s;i&s;ts of po&s;itive <HI>Mat|ters of Fact,</HI> which teaches what has been often &s;ucce&s;sful in the <HI>&s;ame</HI> Circum&s;tances; and I may be bold to &s;ay, that Po&s;itive Phy&s;ick, regulated by <HI>Method,</HI> is the true Phy&s;ick.</P>
<P>School Phy&s;ick, enables Practitioners to make &s;mart Repartees, to come off hand|&s;omely in a controverted Point; and the other makes us <HI>&s;en&s;ible</HI> and Prudent, &s;o as to order nothing but what's <HI>convenient:</HI> The out makes us Head&s;trong and Opinionative, and the other makes us <HI>hone&s;t</HI> Phy&s;icians, who &s;eek for nothing but how to inform our &s;elves, and to be u&s;eful: The one &s;eeks for <HI>Eva&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ons</HI> how to defend him&s;elf under a Di&s;appointment, and the other for Medi|cines to <HI>Cure</HI> Di&s;tempers: The one con&s;ults his <HI>Ideas,</HI> and the other con&s;ults his <HI>Rea&s;on</HI> and <HI>Experience:</HI> The one makes <HI>Pedants,</HI> and the other <HI>Phy&s;icians.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">A Chymi|cal Elixir, and its Operation.</NOTE>And fir&s;t, my <HI>Chymical Elixir,</HI> is in its own Nature peculiarly adapted to the <HI>Cure</HI> of the Cholick, becau&s;e its innate vertues are powerful in allaying <HI>Pains,</HI> taking away the <HI>Cau&s;e</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;e, and re-invigorating the Patient's <HI>Strength,</HI> and refre&s;hing his <HI>Spirits,</HI> by which means, and not by any <HI>Narcotick</HI> quality in the Medicine, Nature is enabled to expel the Morbifick Matter lodg d in the Nervous <HI>Plexus</HI>'s of the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> and to &s;ubdue and conquer the Di&s;ea&s;e. This <HI>Elixir</HI> al&s;o is endued with an excellent Quality, to <HI>Purify</HI> the Blood and <HI>Nervous</HI>
<PB N="29" REF="28">Liquors, and keep them in a due and regular <HI>Cra&s;is,</HI> in order to prevent the <HI>engendring</HI> of Morbifick Matter; Strengthens the <HI>Brain</HI> and the <HI>Nervous</HI> Foldings of the <HI>Abdomen,</HI> and removes the pre&s;ent <HI>Procatarxis</HI> of the Cholick, and hinders the Inva&s;ions of Pains for the Future, &s;o that they &s;hall &s;eldom or never return afterwards.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">How to be taken, and its happy Effects.</NOTE>Which <HI>Elixir</HI> is to be taken, Ten Drops at a time, when a&s;&s;aulted by Cholick Pains, in Five or Six Spoonfuls of Generous Wine, &s;mooth clear Ale, or well brew d Table-Beer, every half Hour till the Pain is abated, and then forbear taking any more Drops for that time, unle&s;s the Pain returns. This Quantity of Drops is proper for <HI>Men;</HI> but the <HI>Fair</HI> Sex mu&s;t take but Five or Six Drops at a time, in Two or Three Spoon|fuls of either of the above mention'd Li|quors, ob&s;erving the &s;ame Rules as are given to Men. But if the Sick are enclined to Vo|mit up whatever they take, let the Patient take the &s;ame quantity of Drops in a &s;ma<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">er quantity of Liquor. Some Per&s;ons of both Sexes can take a greater number of Drops than others; and in violent Fits of the Cholick, if the Patient has not ea&s;e with a &s;mall number of Drops, let them add two Drops every time they take them, till ea&s;y, then take no more that time. As to the quantity of the Drops the Patient is the proper judge, who finding what number of Drops be&s;t agrees with his Con&s;titu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ion, his own <HI>Rea&s;on</HI> will induce him in all Effects, to &s;tick to that Quantity.</P>
<P>When either Man or Woman takes my E|lixir in the Day time, let them lye down upo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> a Bed, di&s;po&s;e them&s;elves to <HI>Re&s;t,</HI> and
<PB N="30" REF="29">if they find their <HI>Stomachs</HI> any way di&s;order'd, the longer they <HI>repo&s;e,</HI> the &s;ooner they will find Refre&s;hment and <HI>Ea&s;e.</HI></P>
<P>If the Sick enter into a cour&s;e of taking my <HI>Elixir,</HI> to eradicate this Di&s;temper and put a final end to his tormenting Pains, let him take Four Drops at Night when he is going to Bed, in a Gla&s;s of &s;ome, of the <HI>Vehicle</HI> afore named, or in <HI>Bohe Tea,</HI> and continue &s;o to do, by adding One Drop every &s;ucce&s;&s;ive Night, till he has imbibed 20, 30, or 40 Drops; or at lea&s;t the certain number that agrees with him, and adhere to that, till he finds him&s;elf recover'd; always lying long in Bed in the <HI>Morning,</HI> that the <HI>Elixir</HI> may the &s;ooner produce its de&s;ired happy Effect.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">An Ad|verti&s;e|ment to Water-Drinkers.</NOTE>Further, if the Sick has at any time, found &s;ome Benefit by drinking <HI>Spaw-Water,</HI> and is de&s;irous to continue it, becau&s;e his Bowels are too Hot, let him put Six Drops of my <HI>Elixir</HI> into half a Pint of <HI>Spaw-Water,</HI> and drink it going to Bed, for a Month to|gether; for, this <HI>Elixir</HI> is the <HI>be&s;t</HI> Medicine in the World, to make all <HI>Mineral</HI> Waters pa&s;s off well and quickly by Urine or Seige; which if they &s;tay <HI>long</HI> in the Body, by taking up their Quarters in the <HI>Head</HI> or <HI>Feet,</HI> they will cau&s;e the <HI>Vertigo,</HI> or <HI>Gout,</HI> as is often found by dreadful Experience. Which may &s;erve as a <HI>cautionary. Adverti&s;ement,</HI> to all that accu&s;tom them&s;elves for Diver&s;ion or Ne|ce&s;&s;ity &s;ake, to drink <HI>Tunbridge, Ep&s;om, Dul|lege, Ken&s;ington, I&s;lington, North-Hall, Bath, Northampton-&s;hire, Derby-&s;hire,</HI> or <HI>York-&s;hire-Waters,</HI> that they always carry a &s;mall Bottle of my <HI>Elixir</HI> along with them, for preven|tion of &s;uch ill Accidents as frequently come
<PB N="31" REF="30">to pa&s;s, by drinking tho&s;e Waters alone, and to effect more <HI>&s;afely, certainly</HI> and <HI>&s;peedi|ly</HI> their <HI>Intentions</HI> in drinking tho&s;e Mineral Waters, which for want of u&s;ing my <HI>Elixir</HI> with them, generally prove ineffectual.</P>
<P>This <HI>Elixir,</HI> a name taken from the <HI>Arabick</HI> Word <HI>Elee&s;chir,</HI> &s;ignifying Powerful, is al&s;o effectual again&s;t the Stone, Gravel, and Bloody Urine; &s;tops Vomiting and a Loo&s;ne&s;s, and is a proper Medicine again&s;t Chatars, Coughs, and all Di&s;ea&s;es incident to the Head and Brea&s;t. It continues its whole Vertue in all <HI>Climates,</HI> and con&s;e|quently is fit to be carried, as it has been, to the <HI>Ea&s;t</HI> or <HI>We&s;t-Indies,</HI> to any of the <HI>Northern Countries,</HI> the <HI>Mediteranean,</HI> or the <HI>South-Seas.</HI> It will la&s;t more than <HI>Twenty Years,</HI> and no Family that has <HI>Experienc'd</HI> its <HI>Vertues</HI> in many others, as well as this Di|&s;temper, will be without it.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Au|thor's Cor|dia<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Cho|lick Waters.</NOTE>And &s;ince in this Di&s;ea&s;e, <HI>all things,</HI> tho' properly enough contrived and invented, do not agree with <HI>all Per&s;ons,</HI> nor plea&s;e in in the &s;ame <HI>Form</HI> of Compo&s;ition, and that &s;ome <HI>Palates</HI> di&s;reli&s;h what others imbibe with Plea&s;ure, &s;o there is &s;ometimes a <HI>Ne|ce&s;&s;ity</HI> of changing and altering Medicines in re&s;pect of their Form, as well as Ingre|dients in their Compo&s;ition, that they may more <HI>effectually</HI> operate upon the different <HI>vicious</HI> Humours, and on the <HI>various</HI> Parts affected.</P>
<P>To an&s;wer all the&s;e Ends, I invented my <HI>Cordial Anticholical Water,</HI> who&s;e vertues far exceed the common Tincture of <HI>Steel</HI> and of <HI>Antimony</HI> and <HI>Amber,</HI> &s;o much extoll'd in the Cure of the Cholick; becau&s;e after a <HI>peculiar</HI> manner, it gives <HI>Ea&s;e</HI> by expelling
<PB N="32" REF="31">the <HI>vi&s;cous Recrements</HI> in the great Me&s;ente|rick <HI>Plexus,</HI> to which the <HI>Inte&s;tines</HI> are an|nexed, and allays the griping Pains that follow the irregular Cure of <HI>Fevers,</HI> which are caus'd, by transferring the Morbifick Matter to the <HI>Glandules</HI> of the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> and the &s;ub&s;equent irritation of its <HI>Nerves.</HI> This <HI>Anticholical</HI> Water, or <HI>Solar</HI> Liquor, has al&s;o both a <HI>Diuretick</HI> and <HI>Carminative</HI> Quality, and has admirable effects, both in <HI>Tender</HI> and <HI>Robu&s;t</HI> Con&s;titutions, and I often give it with great Succe&s;s, either it &s;elf, or mix'd with other proper <HI>Specificks,</HI> as a Spur in Hot <HI>Di&s;cra&s;ies</HI> of the <HI>Vi&s;cera</HI> with a pre|dominancy of <HI>adu&s;t</HI> Sulphur, as al&s;o in Flit|ting, Scorbutical, and irregular <HI>Boilings</HI> of the Blood and <HI>Nervous juice,</HI> which &s;eldom or never fails of doing good in the mo&s;t de&s;perate Ca&s;es I have met with, in many Years Practice.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">How to be taken.</NOTE>This Water is to be taken by Two or Three Spoonfuls at any time, when the Sick is grieved with the Cholick; either by it &s;elf, or put into a Gla&s;s of warm Ale, or burnt White-Wine, and being <HI>repeated</HI> as occa&s;ion requires, the <HI>Phy&s;ician</HI> will accom|pli&s;h his main end, and the <HI>Patient</HI> if he is a Per&s;on of common Ingenuity, Gratitud<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> and Hone&s;ty, will not grudge his Expenc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> of Time or Money, in purcha&s;ing &s;o effica|cious Remedy.</P>
<P>The Third <HI>No&s;trum</HI> I employ for the Cure of the Cholick, I call <HI>Pillulae Anticolicae,</HI> or <HI>Anticholical</HI> Pills; They are compounded of the choice&s;t Ingredients in the whole <HI>Ma|teria Medica,</HI> and require a long time and great Care and Pains in their Preparation, the <HI>Ma&s;s</HI> being an <HI>Extract</HI> and no common
<PB N="33" REF="32">Compo&s;ition, as will appear in their <HI>Opera|tion,</HI> and the happy <HI>effects</HI> produced by them. Now you having read in the foregoing Di&s;|cour&s;e, that in &s;ome Ca&s;es, and e&s;pecially when the <HI>Inte&s;tines</HI> are much contracted by <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> Matter contain'd in them, that <HI>Purg|ing</HI> Medicines are not to be u&s;ed; and that <HI>all other</HI> Ca&s;es, for the Cure of the Cholick, &s;trong <HI>Catharticks</HI> are ab&s;olutely nece&s;&s;ary; to avoid the&s;e extreams, I have cho&s;en the <HI>Golden mean,</HI> and &s;o contrived my <HI>Anticho|lical Pills,</HI> by mixing attenuating and mol|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ifying Ingredients with Purgatives, that they will Work but <HI>gently,</HI> tho' very <HI>ef|fectually,</HI> in order to di&s;cu&s;s or expel the <HI>Peccant</HI> Humours by degrees, without of|fering <HI>Violence</HI> to Nature, by being over <HI>ha&s;ty</HI> in th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Cure, and to that end admini|&s;tring over powerful Purgatives, which ra|ther weaken the Patient, than mitigate his Pains, or dimini&s;h his Di&s;temper. But <HI>my Pills</HI> are <HI>Hermetically</HI> compounded, and at the &s;ame time both throw out the &s;harp <HI>of|fen<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ing</HI> Humours, corroborate the <HI>Stomach,</HI> fortify the <HI>Spirits,</HI> and &s;trengthen the whole Body again&s;t the future Inva&s;ion of the Di&s;|ea&s;e, as the only &s;afe and ea&s;y way to a per|fect Cure, which the&s;e Pills, taken accord|ing to the following Directions, very &s;eldom <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="3 letters">ve behind them.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Directions for taking the Pills.</NOTE>They are to be taken, one pill late at Night, at the time of going to Re&s;t, every third or fourth Night, and if that Pill does not Work pretty early in the Morning, take one or two Pills more every two Hours till they Operate gently, but if it makes the Patient Sick in his Stomach, and doth not Purge him, let him Di&s;&s;olve an
<PB N="34" REF="33">Ounce of <HI>Ep&s;om</HI> Salt, or &s;ix Drams of the <HI>Le|nitive Electuary,</HI> in a Pint of Water Gruel, or Mutton-Broath, and drink it Blood-warm, the Pills will have the &s;ame effect, if they are forced to be purg'd off; Two, Three, or Four Stools is &s;ufficient for one time: Keep very warm, and drink nothing cold that Day. After taking them, let the Sick drink large draughts of thin <HI>Chicken</HI> Broath, <HI>Mutton</HI> Broath, or Water Gruel, or for want of them <HI>Po&s;&s;et Drink,</HI> to dilute the &s;harp Humours, ca&s;t them out, or their <HI>A|crimony</HI> being taken off, reduce them to a better Temper: Which you will &s;oon find, if this Cour&s;e is duly repeated, as often as there is occa&s;ion, and when there is none, take no more Pills, for I don't give them for Lucre of <HI>Money,</HI> but to an&s;wer the In|tention of <HI>Healing,</HI> for therein con&s;i&s;ts my Intere&s;t. The&s;e Pills are good for the Scurvy, Pains in any part of the Body, King's Evil, corrupt Humours in any Part of the Body, the Itch, Leprofie, Old Ulcers, Worms, Gravel, Stones and in other Ca&s;es where Purging is nece&s;&s;ary.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Fourth Remedy.</NOTE>Tho&s;e Days wherein the Patient does not Purge, I give a <HI>Cordial Electuary,</HI> which I call <HI>Electuarium Anticolica,</HI> or my <HI>Anticholical Electuary,</HI> which is the <HI>Fourth</HI> Remedy for the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, and which &s;eldom fails, if the Di&s;ea&s;e is Cureable, this <HI>Electuary</HI> being indued with &s;uch rare, uncommon and well experienc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d <HI>Vertues,</HI> agreeable to the Dictates of <HI>Nature</HI> and <HI>Art,</HI> and &s;o &s;ignifi|cantly adapted to the Cure of the <HI>Cholick,</HI> in all its various kinds, where purging is ne|ce&s;&s;ary or unnece&s;&s;ary and dangerous, that the Patient will &s;eldom be perfectly cured with|out
<PB N="35" REF="34">it; becau&s;e as I have found by repeated Experience, that when all other Remedies pre&s;cribed by the be&s;t Hands have been in|effectual, this <HI>Electuary</HI> has done the Work, by corroborating the Stomach, correcting its vicious Fermentation, retrieving its depraved Appetite, and re&s;toring its almo&s;t lo&s;t <HI>Tone</HI> to a regular and &s;anative <HI>Cra&s;is.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Directions for taking this Ele|ctuary.</NOTE>This <HI>Electuary</HI> is &s;ometimes al&s;o to be taken in the Morning on an empty Sto|mach: Its <HI>Do&s;e</HI> is about the quantity of a <HI>Nutmeg,</HI> fa&s;ting an Hour after it, and again at Four or Five in the Afternoon, for 10, 15, 20, or 30 Days, when you u&s;e no Purgatives. Eat what Dyet is mo&s;t <HI>nouri&s;hing</HI> and &s;its <HI>light</HI> upon the Stomach, and ab&s;tain from nothing &s;o much as <HI>Milk</HI> and <HI>Stale</HI> Beer. And now I might be Very Copious, in the Commendation and Prai&s;e of the&s;e <HI>Four Re|medies,</HI> invented by, and I believe only known to my <HI>&s;elf,</HI> and are di&s;po&s;ed of at no Place, but my Dwelling-Hou&s;e; but that Per&s;ons who know me not, may not think I <HI>harangue</HI> to promote my own <HI>Profit</HI> in &s;elling them, I &s;hall wave it for the pre&s;ent, and leave every Man that buys and u&s;es them, to give them what Character they De&s;erve. For when I have &s;aid all I can, <HI>Wi&s;e Men</HI> will not regard what is <HI>&s;aid</HI> of them, but what <HI>Cures</HI> have been, and may be accom|pli&s;h'd by them. And from hence I pro|ceed to Ob&s;ervations, and <HI>Examples</HI> of Per|&s;ons cured of the Cholick, by the regular u&s;e of my afore named Remedies of which its needle&s;s to give you great Numbers, tho' I am plentifully furni&s;h'd with them; becau&s;e the Publick bas almo&s;t Weekly notice of Per&s;ons cured by me in
<PB N="36" REF="35">Certificates under the Hands of my Patien<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">s, well atte&s;ted, and Printed in the Publick News Papers.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Examples of Per&s;ons Cured.</NOTE>A Gentlewoman of good Reputation, ex|treamly afflicted with the <HI>Cholick</HI> for many Years, after &s;he had taken, as &s;he thought, the be&s;t Advice that could be given in <HI>Lon|don,</HI> was recommended to my Care for the Cure of her Cholick. I gave her <HI>Antimonial Emeticks, Chalybeats, Catharticks</HI> and <HI>Alcalious</HI> Medicines, but without any effect, &s;he con|tinuing &s;till in a &s;ad and deplorable Condi|tion. While &s;he was empty, &s;he had an abatement of her Pain; but &s;he no &s;ooner Eat, but her Pains return'd and continued till her Food was Dige&s;ted. At the &s;ame time when &s;he labour'd under this Di&s;ea&s;e, &s;he was often overwhelm'd with <HI>Vapours;</HI> often complain'd of Pain between her Shoul|ders and in other Parts, and well &s;he might; for con&s;idering the <HI>Scituation</HI> of the Parts, I found that when &s;he was full, her Stomach pre&s;&s;ed upon the <HI>Pancreas,</HI> which is a &s;ort of a <HI>Pillow</HI> to keep the Stomach from rubbing again&s;t the <HI>Vertebre</HI>'s of the Back, and &s;oon after di&s;cover'd, that the <HI>Pancreas</HI> and <HI>Pilorus</HI> were the Parts affected, occa&s;ion'd by the Acidity of the <HI>Pancreas</HI> and the Unctiou&s;ne&s;s of the <HI>Gall,</HI> which had produced an <HI>&V;lcer</HI> in the <HI>Pancreas,</HI> which with the <HI>Pylorus</HI> was full of Matter, and when I had interchangeably given her my forenamed <HI>Arcana</HI>'s, &s;he threw out at times upward and downward, a prodigious quantity of <HI>Pus,</HI> and then ad|mini&s;tring proper Pacificks and Healers, &s;he was perfectly cured, retired into the Country, where &s;he continues in Health to this Day.</P>
<PB N="37" REF="36">
<P>This Gentlewoman being unwilling to have her Name publi&s;h'd, I will not di&s;|obtige her in doing it; and &s;hall take this opportunity to &s;atisfie the Publick, that I never Print any Per&s;on's Name without their leave, or a Te&s;timony under the Pa|tient's Hand; but if any Per&s;on &s;eems to <HI>doubt</HI> the truth of it, his <HI>curio&s;ity</HI> may be &s;atisfied by her Brother, a <HI>Merchant,</HI> who was an Eye-Witne&s;s of the Cure, and dwells at <HI>Humberton,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of <HI>Hackney,</HI> in <HI>Middle&s;ex.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Grace,</HI> Wife of <HI>Thomas Hogges</HI> Weaver, dwelling in <HI>Church-&s;treet,</HI> in <HI>Coverlet-&s;treet,</HI> next Hou&s;e to the Sign of the <HI>Lyons,</HI> was troubled with the <HI>Cholick</HI> &s;ix whole Years together, in which time &s;he had the Ad|vice of &s;everal <HI>Phy&s;itians,</HI> but they doing her no good, at la&s;t &s;he apply'd her &s;elf to me, and I cured her out of mere <HI>Charity,</HI> who has &s;ince been &s;o grateful, as to recommend &s;everal other Patients to me, who were in better Circum&s;tances in regard of Wealth, who all as well as her &s;elf have <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">een perfectly Cured by the u&s;e of my afore|named Medicines.</P>
<P>A Trade&s;man in the City of <HI>London,</HI> who had &s;uffer'd intolerable <HI>Cholical</HI> Pains, and had taken &s;everal Medicines from his own <HI>Phy&s;itian</HI> and <HI>Apothecary</HI> for a con&s;iderable time, was induced to apply him&s;elf to me, and I gave him Ea&s;e <HI>immediately,</HI> and in a very &s;hort time after, perfectly cured him. Tho&s;e that doubt the truth of this matter, if they think &s;it to enquire of me, I &s;hall di|rect them to the Per&s;on him&s;elf that was
<PB N="38" REF="37">Cured, who will readily atte&s;t the Truth of what I have here a&s;&s;erted, to the Satisfacti|on of any Per&s;on, that is not obliged by <HI>Intere&s;t</HI> to &s;hew him&s;elf <HI>Incredulous.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Cholick in the Sto|mach.</NOTE>Having now fini&s;h'd what I had to &s;ay of an <HI>Accidental</HI> Cholick, according to the Me|thod propo&s;ed, I am obliged to treat of the Cholick as <HI>complicated</HI> or joined with other Di&s;ea&s;es, and that which leads the Van, is the <HI>Stomachical Chotick,</HI> and that very ju&s;tly, becau&s;e the <HI>Minera</HI> of all Chronical Di&s;|ea&s;es are to be &s;ought in the Stomach: And if the upper <HI>Orifice</HI> of it, which is of <HI>exqui&s;ite</HI> Sen&s;e, by rea&s;on of the intermixture of <HI>Nerves,</HI> with which it is plentifully furni&s;h'd from the <HI>vaga &s;exta,</HI> Branches whereof being communicated to the <HI>Heart,</HI> that noble part being affected, then the Di&s;ea&s;e is called in Greek <GAP DESC="foreign"> vel <GAP DESC="foreign">, and in Latin <HI>Cardiacus dolor, the Pain of the Heart;</HI> but if the lower Orifice called <HI>Pylorus</HI> be affected, it is called <HI>Dolor, &s;eu Colica Ventriculi, Pain, or the Cholick in the Stomach,</HI> more e&s;pecially if it proceed from <HI>Wind.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of the Cholick in the Sto|mach.</NOTE>The <HI>Internal</HI> Cau&s;es of this Di&s;ea&s;e, &s;ome|times proceed from great <HI>Oppletion</HI> and Pain of the Stomach, &s;ometimes from frequent and violent <HI>Vomiting,</HI> which ari&s;es from the <HI>Chyle</HI> there degenerated into a Ma&s;s of Cor|ruption; but oftner from the Morbifick Matter brought thither, either by the con|veyance of the <HI>Blood,</HI> or al&s;o of the <HI>Nervous Juice,</HI> and either depo&s;ed within the <HI>Cavity</HI> of the Stomach, or fix'd in the <HI>Plexus</HI>'s of the <HI>Nerves,</HI> and in the <HI>Membranes</HI> appertaining to it. Sometimes <HI>Worms</HI> gnawing the <HI>Tunicles</HI> of the Stomach cau&s;e this Di&s;ea&s;e, or <HI>Wind</HI>
<PB N="39" REF="38">lodg'd in the Cavity of the Stomach, which cau&s;es Swellings and painful Di&s;ten&s;ion, or from &s;harp <HI>Phlegm</HI> or Green and Black <HI>Choler;</HI> who&s;e &s;harp Vapours cau&s;e Pain, or from cor|rupt Matter from an <HI>Impo&s;thume</HI> in the Liver, or the Brea&s;t, <HI>Di&s;ea&s;es</HI> of the Stomach, and Parts adjoining; ill <HI>Humours</HI> from the whole Body as in Fevers, <HI>Choler</HI> from the <HI>Liver, Me|lancholly</HI> from the <HI>Spleen,</HI> Salt <HI>Phlegm</HI> from the <HI>Head;</HI> all the&s;e may be the Cau&s;es of the <HI>Cho|lick</HI> in the Stomach.</P>
<P>The <HI>External</HI> Cau&s;es of this Malady, may be corrupt Nouri&s;hment, Viands too Hot that breed Wind or Choler: <HI>Meat</HI> taken in too large quantity, <HI>Poy&s;on,</HI> or &s;trong &s;harp and dangerous Medicines <HI>uncorrected.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms of the Cho|lick in the Stomach.</NOTE><HI>Diagno&s;tick</HI> Signs, are, Pain in the <HI>En&s;i|formis,</HI> or lower part of the Brea&s;t-Bone, which &s;ignifie that the <HI>upper Orifice</HI> of the Stomach is affected with very &s;harp Pain, that will not &s;uffer the Patient to take any <HI>Re&s;t,</HI> and &s;ometimes cau&s;e an inveterate <HI>Headach,</HI> the <HI>Megrim, Vertigo</HI> and the <HI>Epi|lep&s;y.</HI> In the other Parts of the Stomach the Symptoms are not &s;o violent, but are truly <HI>Cholical,</HI> and exactly re&s;emble that Di&s;ea&s;e in its utmo&s;t Latitude.</P>
<P><HI>Progno&s;tick</HI> Symptoms are ominous, for this Di&s;ea&s;e is more <HI>danger<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">us</HI> than any other Di&s;|ea&s;e of the Stomach, and the Danger is <HI>greater</HI> if it is accompanied with a <HI>Fever,</HI> for in &s;uch a ca&s;e, according to <HI>Hippocrates,</HI> Death is at hand. Its lea&s;t dangerous if it proceeds from Worms; tho' even in that, &s;ometimes dangerous Symptoms appear and the Patient dies. In &s;hort, the <HI>Progno&s;ticks</HI> are u&s;ually the Symptoms of <HI>Hypocondriack Illne&s;s;</HI> and if they happen upon the <HI>recovery</HI> of a Di&s;ea&s;e,
<PB N="40" REF="39">portends its <HI>relap&s;e;</HI> if they come from <HI>Wind</HI> that cannot be removed a <HI>Dry Drop&s;ie</HI> fol|lows. If they &s;tink horribly, they are very Malignant and <HI>Contagious.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cure of a Cholick in the Sto|mach.</NOTE>The method of Curing a <HI>Stomachical Cho|lick,</HI> if it be not grown <HI>Ob&s;tinate, Inveterate,</HI> and beyond the <HI>Power</HI> of Medicines to give Relief, is by con&s;idering the <HI>Cau&s;e</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;e, to pre&s;cribe Medicines that are pro|per to remove it.</P>
<P>If <HI>Wind</HI> is the Cau&s;e, <HI>Carminative</HI> Cly&s;ters are exhibited, to di&s;cu&s;s it and moderate the <HI>violent</HI> Pains in the Stomach cau&s;ed by it: And if the <HI>Wind</HI> be accompanied with flu&s;h|ings in the Face and exce&s;&s;ive Heat, <HI>Spirit of Nitre dulci&s;ied with Spirit of Wine, and impreg|nated with the Vertue of Carminative Simples after</HI> Sylvius<HI>'s Method,</HI> is &s;aid to be an incomparable Remedy. Inveterate <HI>acid</HI> Belchings are put off, <HI>by five or &s;ix Pepper Corns being taken every Morning Fa&s;ting.</HI> If the Wind proceed from a thick, &s;tubborn <HI>Mucilage, A&s;thmatical Syrups, and</HI> Michael<HI>'s Elixir for the Stomach</HI> are very proper; to which you may add Externally, <HI>Fomentations with Oil of Chamomel, and of the Carminative Seeds: Or with a mixture of Ani|&s;eed-Water, Spirit of Wine Camphorated and Treacle.</HI></P>
<P>If a <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> &s;tinking, or otherwi&s;e offen|&s;ive matter be ca&s;t up by <HI>Vomit,</HI> and there be <HI>&s;u&s;picion</HI> that the Cau&s;e lies in the <HI>Cavity</HI> of the <HI>Stomach,</HI> 'tis proper to give <HI>a gentle Vomit, of Wine of Squills, or of Salt of Vitriol;</HI> or the offending Humours may be purg'd off by Stool, by <HI>Stomachical</HI> Catharticks adapted <HI>pro re nata.</HI> But if the Matter &s;ticks deeply and firmly within the <HI>Membranes,</HI> or foldings of the Nerves, <HI>Diaphoreticks or Specificks that
<PB N="41" REF="40">moderate the efferve&s;cencies of the Salts</HI> are more prevalent, and ought to be admini&s;tred at proper times, as the Phy&s;ician employ'd <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">hall find occa&s;ion: Not forgetting, twice or thrice a Day to apply <HI>Fomentations</HI> to the Region of the Stomach, with Woolen Cloths dipt in the warm'd Liquid Medicine la&s;t above named, and wrung forth; for that will much contribute to the abatement of the Patient's griping, intolerable Pains.</P>
<P>In the next place it will be expected that here I &s;hould &s;ay &s;omething of a <HI>Stomachical Cholick</HI> cau&s;ed by <HI>Worms</HI> gnawing the <HI>Tunicles</HI> of the Stomach, but I &s;hall wholly omit it at pre&s;ent; becau&s;e the next <HI>Phy&s;ical</HI> Di&s;cour&s;e I &s;hall publi&s;h, &s;hall be a <HI>Treati&s;e of the Worms,</HI> which I am now preparing for the <HI>Pre&s;s.</HI> In the mean time, if any Per&s;on, <HI>Young</HI> or <HI>Old,</HI> that is troubled with them, and de&s;ires to be rid of tho&s;e <HI>Vexations</HI> and dangerous <HI>Inmates,</HI> that render Life &s;o unea&s;y, if he plea&s;e to come or &s;end to me, he may be &s;upplied with <HI>Antivermetick</HI> Medicines of my own preparing, that will effectually <HI>Eject</HI> tho&s;e <HI>vile</HI> Inhabitants, under every denomina|tion.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Au|thor's own Medicines.</NOTE>But to return from this Digre&s;&s;ion, the Method I have &s;hewn in the general practice of Phy&s;ick, by the be&s;t Phy&s;icians of the pre&s;ent Age, in the foregoing Paragraphs, is what I ob&s;erve my &s;elf, tho' the Medicines I give are entirely of my own <HI>Inventing, Compounding</HI> and <HI>Preparing,</HI> and the <HI>Effi|cacy</HI> whereof I can rely upon for a Cure, (if curable) of this dangerous Di&s;ea&s;e; for tho' in all <HI>Cholical</HI> Di&s;tempers my <HI>Elixir, Cho|lick-Water, Pills and Electuary,</HI> will have their Turns, yet am I not unprovided of <HI>other</HI>
<PB N="42" REF="41">Medicines to a&s;&s;i&s;t effectually in the Cure, When the Cholick is <HI>complicated</HI> with other Di&s;ea&s;es, and con&s;equently indigitates the u&s;e of others, as the Cholick <HI>varies</HI> in its <HI>Name, Cau&s;e</HI> and <HI>Parts affected.</HI></P>
<P>For the&s;e Rea&s;ons and becau&s;e in <HI>Sto|machical Cholicks,</HI> proceeding from Vi&s;cous &s;tinking Matter lodg'd in the Cavity of the Stomach, a Vomit &s;eems ab&s;olutely nece&s;|&s;ary, to di&s;lodge the offending Humour; I am always provided of an <HI>Emetick</HI> of &s;uch an univer&s;al Vertue, that it an&s;wers all the <HI>Intentions of Nature and Art</HI> in Vomiting, and leaves no <HI>Relicks</HI> for another Inva&s;ion behind it. Which Medicine will never lo&s;e its Ver|tue, and con&s;equently may be &s;ent to the remote&s;t parts of the <HI>&V;niver&s;e,</HI> and private <HI>Families</HI> may keep it by them to u&s;e when they have occa&s;ion.</P>
<P>Where the corrupted Matter in a <HI>Stomachi|cal Cholick</HI> &s;ticks firm and deep within the <HI>Membranes</HI> or Foldings of the <HI>Nerves,</HI> and indigitates the u&s;e of <HI>Diaphoreticks,</HI> or &s;uch Medicines as moderate the efferve&s;cencies of the <HI>Salts:</HI> For tho&s;e purpo&s;es I have a <HI>Mi|neral</HI> Remedy, which I exhibit &s;ometimes in <HI>Powder,</HI> other whiles in the form of an <HI>Electuary,</HI> and at other times in a <HI>Decoction</HI> or Syrup, as they be&s;t agree with the Pa|tient's <HI>Palate,</HI> which works almo&s;t miracu|lou&s;ly in this Di&s;ea&s;e, and &s;o clean&s;e, purify and &s;trengthen the Stomach, and a&s;&s;i&s;t it in the Work of <HI>Fermentation,</HI> that it expels all noxious humours whatever, and retains what conduces to a <HI>vigorous</HI> con&s;titution and a <HI>durable</HI> &s;tate of Health.</P>
<P>The&s;e great things I am &s;en&s;ible my nu|merous Enemies, which are chiefly Per&s;ons
<PB N="43" REF="42">of my own <HI>Profe&s;&s;ion,</HI> or &s;uch unthinking People as are <HI>prejudiced</HI> by their malicious fal&s;e &s;tories, will call idle, vain <HI>Bo&s;ting,</HI> but tho&s;e that have experienced and <HI>tried</HI> my Medicines, will do m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> ju&s;tice in a mo|de&s;ter and ju&s;ter Character, and e&s;teem my Remedies as <HI>Non-Pareils.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Hy|&s;terical Cholick.</NOTE>This Di&s;ea&s;e being commonly known by the tormenting <HI>Pains</HI> that always accompany it, might rea&s;onably &s;ave me the labour of giving, and my Reader the lo&s;s of time in peru&s;ing them: However, in compliance with my Promi&s;e, I &s;hall give him one of the many Ob&s;ervations I have made, and Ex|amples I am able to produce.</P>
<P><HI>John Gregory Cabinet-Maker,</HI> in <HI>Philip-Lane,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of St. <HI>Alphage,</HI> near <HI>London-Wall,</HI> being grieved with the Cholick in his <HI>Stomach,</HI> attended with extraordinary Pain in the <HI>En&s;iformis,</HI> or lower part of the Brea&s;t Bone; which was &s;ufficient rea&s;on to induce me to be of Opinion, that the <HI>upper Orifice</HI> of the Stomach was affected; and giving him proper Medicines of my own, he no &s;ooner took them according to my Di|rections, but he found <HI>ea&s;e immediately,</HI> and continuing the u&s;e of them a very &s;hort time, he was re&s;tored to his former Health, and was able to follow his Bu&s;ine&s;s, which he was uncapable of doing for Five Months time, before he applied him&s;elf to me, tho' he had taken many Medicines of others, without receiving any Benefit by them; but now enjoys perfect Health, the only comfort of Life.</P>
<P>This Di&s;ea&s;e, called by the Greeks <GAP DESC="foreign">, and by the Latins <HI>&V;teri Stangulatio</HI>
<PB N="44" REF="43">or <HI>Colica Hy&s;tericalis, the Hi&s;terical Cholick, or Fits of the Mother,</HI> is not to be imputed to the A&s;cent or <HI>Ri&s;ing</HI> of the Womb, accord|ing to the vulgar expre&s;&s;ion: Nor to the Impetuous ru&s;hing of the Blood into the <HI>Lungs;</HI> for the effect truly called <HI>Hy&s;terical,</HI> is chiefly and primarily <HI>Convul&s;ive,</HI> and de|pends principally on the <HI>Brain</HI> and <HI>genus Nervo&s;um</HI> being affected, and is produced by the explo&s;ion of the Animal Spirits as are other Convul&s;ive Motions, and whatever di&s;order or irregularities happen el&s;e about the motion of the Blood they are only Se|condary and depend on the <HI>Convul&s;ions</HI> of the <HI>Vi&s;cera.</HI> Nor is this Di&s;ea&s;e only frequent, but &s;o &s;trangely <HI>various,</HI> that it re&s;embles almo&s;t all the Di&s;ea&s;es poor Mortals are in|clin'd to, and generally ends in an <HI>Hemiplegy,</HI> a <HI>Pal&s;ey</HI> on one &s;ide, below the Head, which ob&s;tructs the Animal Spirits in their pa&s;&s;age, and is exactly like an <HI>Appoplexy;</HI> whereby <HI>corpulent</HI> and <HI>old</HI> People are de&s;troyed, be|cau&s;e the <HI>Cortex</HI> of the Brain is &s;topt by a &s;uper abundance of <HI>Phlegm.</HI> In the violent Convul&s;ions that happen in an <HI>Hy&s;terical Cholick,</HI> Women &s;eem to have the <HI>Falling Sickne&s;s,</HI> and &s;ometimes &s;truggle &s;o violently, that tho' at other times their Strength is but ordinary, they can &s;carce be held by all the united Strength of tho&s;e that are about them.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Pathogno|mick Sym|toms.</NOTE>The Symptoms of this Di&s;ea&s;e are <HI>various</HI> and manifold, and &s;eldom agree in divers Women, or happen wholly in the &s;ame man|ner: The mo&s;t common are, Malignant Vapours, exce&s;&s;ive &s;tretching or tearing Pain under the &s;hort Ribs, a <HI>motion</HI> in the lower part of the Belly, and an <HI>A&s;cent,</HI> as it were,
<PB N="45" REF="44">of &s;ome round thing there, fal&s;ly imputed to the <HI>Womb,</HI> then a <HI>Belching</HI> or &s;training to <HI>Vomit,</HI> a di&s;tention of the <HI>Hypocondres,</HI> and a rumbling with a Belching forth of Wind, an <HI>uneven</HI> and for the mo&s;t part <HI>&s;hort</HI> Breath, a <HI>Suffocation</HI> in the Throat, a <HI>Giddine&s;s,</HI> an, inver&s;ion or rolling of the <HI>Eyes,</HI> often <HI>Laugh|ing</HI> or <HI>Weeping</HI> or <HI>Talking Idly;</HI> &s;ometimes a <HI>&s;peechle&s;sne&s;s</HI> and Immobility, with an ob&s;cure or no <HI>Pul&s;e,</HI> and a <HI>Cadaverous</HI> Countenance. Women of all Ages and Conditions are Ob|noxious to this Di&s;ea&s;e, Rich and Poor, Vir|gins, Wives, Widows, and &s;ometimes tho&s;e Symptoms appear in Girls before <HI>Puberty,</HI> and &s;ometimes in Old Woman after their <HI>Men&s;es</HI> are cea&s;ed; and &s;ome learned Phy|&s;icians tells us, that even Men are &s;ometimes troubled with &s;uch kind of <HI>Pa&s;&s;ions.</HI> But,</P>
<P>Tho' the <HI>Hy&s;terical Cholick</HI> often ri&s;es from the <HI>Brain,</HI> yet &s;ometimes it comes by a Cau&s;e <HI>beginning</HI> either in the <HI>Womb,</HI> or in other parts or the <HI>Vi&s;cera,</HI> and in whatever part it &s;eats it &s;elf, it pre&s;ently produces &s;uch Symptoms as <HI>belong to it,</HI> and unle&s;s the Phy|&s;ician is very Skilful, he will be mi&s;taken, and think tho&s;e Symptoms come from &s;ome <HI>E&s;&s;ential</HI> Di&s;temper of this or that Part, and not from an <HI>Hy&s;terick</HI> Cholick; therefore the Symptoms are be&s;t taken from the Part af|fected. But among all the <HI>Diagno&s;tick</HI> Signs of an <HI>Hy&s;terical</HI> Cholick, this is mo&s;t proper and almo&s;t in&s;eparable, <HI>viz.</HI> an <HI>&V;rine</HI> as clear as Rock-Water, which <HI>Hy&s;terical</HI> Women evacuate mo&s;t plentifully, and is in almo&s;t all of them the <HI>Pathognomick</HI> Sign of this Di&s;ea&s;e, which we call <HI>H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;terical</HI> in Women and <HI>Hypocondriacal</HI> in Men; and Women and
<PB N="46" REF="45">Men &s;eldom Recover, till the <HI>Citron</HI> colour'd Urine returns to its <HI>Amber</HI> colour.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Progno|stick Sym|ptoms.</NOTE>If the <HI>Female</HI> Patient, is extraordinarily troubled with <HI>Cholick</HI> griping Pains and <HI>in|ce&s;&s;ant</HI> Vomitings, joined with &s;trong <HI>Con|vul&s;ive</HI> Fits, her <HI>Men&s;es</HI> &s;topt, undergoing violent Contractions and Convul&s;ions, about the parts of the <HI>Mouth,</HI> and <HI>Face,</HI> and <HI>Arms,</HI> and <HI>Legs,</HI> with a <HI>Pale,</HI> Wan Countenance and <HI>trembling</HI> as &s;he walks, and growing every Day wor&s;e than other, her <HI>Ca&s;e</HI> is very <HI>Dangerous</HI> and &s;eldom or never admits of Cure: But if the Convul&s;ions <HI>cea&s;e,</HI> by admini&s;tring proper Medicines, adapted to <HI>Cholick</HI> Pains and <HI>Fits of the Mother</HI> in Con|junction; <HI>Vapours</HI> a&s;cending from the Womb are expell'd, and the <HI>Men&s;es</HI> orderly flow, they are hopeful Indications.</P>
<P>The <HI>Procatartick</HI> or External Cau&s;es of this <HI>complicated</HI> Di&s;ea&s;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of an Hy&s;te|rical Cho|lick.</NOTE> are violent <HI>motions</HI> of the Body, or which is oftner and wor&s;e, violent <HI>Perturbations</HI> of the Mind from &s;ome &s;udden a&s;&s;ault, either of <HI>Anger</HI> or <HI>Grief,</HI> or &s;uch like Pa&s;&s;ions, e&s;pecially as I have &s;aid already, if <HI>&V;rine</HI> clear as <HI>Chri&s;tal</HI> evacuated <HI>copiou&s;l</HI> at &s;ome certain times, makes the <HI>Diagno&s;tick</HI> more manife&s;t. But to the&s;e <HI>Di&s;orders</HI> of the Mind, which are u&s;ually the Cau&s;e of this Di&s;ea&s;e, <HI>Emptine&s;s</HI> of the Sto|mach by rea&s;on of long <HI>Fa&s;ting,</HI> is to be added, and immoderate <HI>Bleeding,</HI> a <HI>Vomit</HI> or <HI>Purge</HI> that has wrought too much. Now having drawn the Picture of this Di&s;ea&s;e, ac|cording to its vulgar <HI>Phenomena;</HI> in the next place, the <HI>Internal,</HI> Efficient Cau&s;es are to be con&s;idered, as well as I can gather them from all the Circum&s;tances joined together: And in my Opinion this Di&s;ea&s;e that I call
<PB N="47" REF="46">an <HI>H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;terical Cholick,</HI> proceeds from a &s;toppage of the <HI>Men&s;es,</HI> a <HI>confu&s;ion</HI> of the Animal Spirits, when too many of them, and contrary to due proportion are violent|ly burried upon this or that part, cau&s;ing Convul&s;ions and Pains, when they ru&s;h up|on Parts of Exqui&s;ite Sen&s;e; to which the cau&s;es of a <HI>Simple</HI> Cholick being added, you have the true Cau&s;es of this Di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
<P>The general method for the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, is, fir&s;t to give pre&s;ent Ea&s;e in the <HI>Paroxi&s;ms,</HI> and then proceed to a Cure. To accompli&s;h both the&s;e <HI>Intentions,</HI> 'tis u&s;ual in the fir&s;t place to apply &s;tinking and &s;trong &s;melling things to the No&s;trils, the <HI>Effluvia</HI>'s of which, repre&s;s and reduce to order the Spirits which are grown too <HI>Wild,</HI> and apt to make <HI>exorbitant</HI> efforts; nay, and di&s;cu&s;s their <HI>Heterogeneous</HI> combination, and often wholly exterminate it. <HI>A&s;&s;a Faetida, Ca&s;to|reum, Galbanum,</HI> tyed in a fine Cloth and held to the No&s;trils are proper; al&s;o <HI>Par|tridges</HI> Feathers, or old <HI>Shoes</HI> burnt, or <HI>Sul|phur</HI> kindled; al&s;o the <HI>Spirit and Oil of Soot and Harts-horn</HI> often give Ea&s;e; but the chief Indication in this Di&s;ea&s;e, is to <HI>&s;trengthen</HI> the Blood which is the fountain of the Spirits; which being done, the invigorated Spirits can pre&s;erve that order which is agreeable to the <HI>Oeconomy</HI> of the whole Body, and the particular Parts. And therefore when the <HI>Ataxy</HI> of the Spirits has vitiated the Hu|mours by long continuance, you mu&s;t fir&s;t <HI>le&s;&s;en</HI> the Humours &s;o corrupted, by <HI>bleeding</HI> and <HI>Purging</HI> if the Patient has &s;ufficient strength, before you endeavour to invigo|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ate the Blood; and which indeed you can
<PB N="48" REF="47">&s;carce do, whil&s;t a <HI>faeculent</HI> heap of Humours lye in the way.</P>
<P>If there be room for a <HI>Vomit,</HI> you mu&s;t always begin with that, e&s;pecially in <HI>Caco|ch<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">mical</HI> Per&s;ons in whom a mighty load of <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> Phlegm &s;ticking to the Folds and Coats of the Stomach, hinders the Vertues of other Medicines. In a few Days after the Vomit, unle&s;s &s;omewhat indicates the contrary; in Women of a <HI>Hot</HI> Tempera|ment open a Vein in the Arm pre&s;ently, or afterward if need be take Blood from the Foot, or the Fundament by <HI>Leeches,</HI> and after the&s;e Evacuations duly performed: <HI>always provided they be indicated,</HI> let a Purge be given three or four Mornings after. Then to <HI>&s;trengthen</HI> the Blood, and con&s;equently &s;upport the Spirits, let <HI>Chalybeates</HI> be ex|hibited to rai&s;e a Volatile <HI>Ferment</HI> in the Va|pid and Languid Blood, that the <HI>Spirits</HI> may be rou&s;ed, which before were pre&s;s'd down by their own Weight. The&s;e Di|rections I think &s;ufficient, without pre&s;cri|bing particular Medicines or their Do&s;es, for he that does not under&s;tand what Me|dicines are proper, in every Di&s;ea&s;e, the quantity to be given, and the manner <HI>How,</HI> and the time <HI>When,</HI> is unfit to practi&s;e Phy|&s;ick; and for tho&s;e who do not pretend to that Skill, they may have <HI>experimented</HI> Me|dicines of me in mo&s;t Di&s;ea&s;es, if they ei|ther plea&s;e to come them&s;elves, or &s;end their Ca&s;es in <HI>Writing,</HI> or by an <HI>Intelligent</HI> Me&s;&s;enger.</P>
<P>For the <HI>Hy&s;terical Cholick,</HI> I have &s;uch ex|cellent and effectual Remedies, the know|ledge and u&s;e where of God and Nature has freely be&s;towed on me, and daily produce
<PB N="49" REF="48">&s;uch <HI>wonderful</HI> Effects by their own Native Goodne&s;s and Efficacy, that I &s;hould be wanting in my <HI>gratitude</HI> to God, <HI>unju&s;t</HI> to my &s;elf and injurious to the Di&s;ea&s;ed part of Mankind, not to make them known to the inqui&s;itive World, &s;ince I don't pre|tend to a <HI>multiplicity</HI> of Medicines, or to more <HI>Art</HI> than others of my own Profe&s;&s;ion, tho I take more <HI>care</HI> than &s;ome others of my my own Profe&s;&s;ion do in <HI>preparing</HI> them and in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ing my &s;elf of &s;uch Medicines as are fit, not to palliate, <HI>but to cure Di&s;ea&s;es, &s;peedily, &s;afely and thoroughly.</HI> Among which in the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e and <HI>Vapours</HI> which attend it, I have a particular <HI>Secret</HI> that has been experienc'd to excel all others, that I have either heard, or read of, in the whole Republick of Phy&s;ick; as I can prove by abundance of In&s;tances, tho' I give here but a few.</P>
<P><HI>Frances Ma&s;h,</HI> dwelling next Hou&s;e to the Sign of the <HI>Three Travellers</HI> in <HI>Kent-&s;treet, Southwark,</HI> being &s;o violently afflicted with a <HI>Hy&s;terick Cholick,</HI> that it was thought it would have been her Death; upon taking my <HI>Remedies,</HI> which I freely gave her, becau&s;e &s;he was but in mean Circum&s;tances, &s;he was perfectly recover'd of her Di&s;temper, and de&s;ired it might <HI>be publi&s;hed</HI> for the good of all People, who &s;uffer under the &s;ame Di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
<P>Mrs. <HI>Poulter,</HI> dwelling at Mr. <HI>Jack&s;on</HI>'s a <HI>Brick-Layer,</HI> in <HI>Mercer s-&s;treet,</HI> next Door to the Sign of the <HI>Angel</HI> in <HI>Long-Acre,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of St. <HI>Martin</HI>'s <HI>in the Fields,</HI> being &s;ore grieved with a <HI>Cholick</HI> and <HI>Vapours,</HI> in&s;omuch that her painful Fits continued &s;everal
<PB N="50" REF="49">Nights together, to that degree that he<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Life was de&s;pair'd of by all that vi&s;ited her being thought pa&s;t recovery; but applyin<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> her &s;elf to me, and God giving a Ble<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;in<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> to my Medicines, &s;he was perfectly c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">ed and continues in as good Health as ever &s;h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> enjoyed in her whole Life, tho' &s;he has no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> taken any Medicines for Eight or Te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Months la&s;t pa&s;t.</P>
<P>A <HI>Gentlewoman</HI> of good Reputation, is, fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Publick good, ready and willing to at+te&s;t the Truth of Two remarkable and e<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">+traordinary Cures, perform'd by taking m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Medicines; one, upon her Father, who w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters"> &s;everely afflicted with the <HI>Cholick</HI> ari&s;ing fro<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Hypocondriack</HI> Effects, which is the &s;ame Di&s;+ea&s;e in Men as <HI>Hy&s;terical</HI> are in Women, an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> the other on her <HI>Daughter,</HI> which was purely <HI>Cholical</HI> the <HI>Stone,</HI> and <HI>Hy&s;terical,</HI> who&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Ca&s;es were both thought very dangerous, b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ome eminently Learned Phy&s;icians, wh<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> attempted their Cure, but without Succe&s;s who afterwards following my Directions i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> taking my Remedies, had the <HI>benefit</HI> of a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> ab&s;olute Cure. If any Per&s;ons de&s;ire it, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall direct them to the Gentlewoman's Ha|bitation, who will &s;atisfy them of the <HI>Trut<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> of what is above a&s;&s;erted.</P>
<P><HI>Mary Wats,</HI> dwelling in <HI>Noble-&s;treet,</HI> nea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Gold&s;miths-Hall,</HI> being &s;eized with the <HI>Ston<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> and an Hy&s;terick Cholick,</HI> which kept her almo&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> in continued Pains, at times for Ten Year<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="MURP" EXTENT="1 letter"> together, and was thought by her &s;elf and others incurable, by giving her my Medi|cines appropriated to that Di&s;temper, &s;he had Relief and an ab&s;olute Cure.</P>
<PB N="51" REF="50">
<P>And &s;ince Experience &s;hews, that &s;toppage of the <HI>Men&s;es,</HI> or &s;uppre&s;&s;ion of the Cour&s;es, is one of the Cau&s;es of a <HI>Hy&s;terick Cholick;</HI> I cannot here forbear to acquaint the World, that I am po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of a <HI>Pouder,</HI> of a long, Curious and Chargeable <HI>Preparation,</HI> which <HI>never</HI> fails to Cure that Di&s;temper, whether in Women, cau&s;ed by the Veins of the <HI>Ma+trix</HI> being ob&s;tructed, &s;o that the <HI>&s;uperfluous</HI> Blood which nature ordain<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d to be <HI>evacuated</HI> that way, having not a free Pa&s;&s;age, returns to the greater <HI>Ve&s;&s;els,</HI> and is circulated with be whole <HI>Ma&s;s of Blood and Humours,</HI> by which they are in time vitiated, to the great prejudice of the Womans Health, in being the Original Cau&s;es of &s;everal other Di&s;ea&s;es as well as the <HI>Hy&s;terick</HI> Cholick. Or if the&s;e <HI>Ob&s;tructions</HI> happen to <HI>Virgins,</HI> and then is called the <HI>Green-&s;ickne&s;s, the White-Fever and the White Jaundice,</HI> becau&s;e the na|tive colour in &s;uch Per&s;ons is very <HI>Pale;</HI> yet a few Grains of this Pouder taken ac|cording to my Directions, will infallibly cure all tho&s;e Di&s;ea&s;es, as all that try it will happily Experience: And for clean&s;ing the Womb, and furthering Conception in <HI>Barren</HI> Women, there is not the like Medicine (I believe) in the World.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Scor|butick Cho|lick.</NOTE> <HI>Colica Scorbuticus,</HI> or the <HI>Scorbutick Cholick.</HI> There's a &s;ort of <HI>Cachexy</HI> reigning in our <HI>Northern</HI> Clymats, who&s;e Symptoms chiefly appearing in the <HI>Hypochondria,</HI> is called the <HI>Hypocondriack Evil,</HI> and when its Symptoms are very fierce and exalted, 'tis named the <HI>Scurvy:</HI> An <HI>Apellation</HI> given it by the <HI>Saxons</HI> in <HI>North Germany,</HI> who are generally afflict|ed with it. 'Tis a bu&s;ie, intermedling, en|croaching Di&s;ea&s;e, that now mingles almo&s;t
<PB N="50" REF="51">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="51" REF="52">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="52" REF="53">with all Chronical Di&s;tempers, and pa&s;&s;es in|conceivably into all parts of the Body; which cau&s;ed <HI>Helmant</HI> to &s;ay of complicated Effects, that <HI>per ignorata &s;eminaria, &amp; initia invi&s;ibilia, by unknown Seminaries, and in vi&s;ible Beginnings,</HI> which is certainly true, for in the&s;e latter times new Di&s;ea&s;es have &s;tarted up, which were unknown to the Antients; becau&s;e they have put on other &s;trange <HI>Sym|ptoms</HI> and <HI>Properties, Quibus larvati incedunt,</HI> with which they walk <HI>di&s;gui&s;ed</HI> and deceive &s;uch Phy&s;icians, as think to Cure Di&s;ea&s;es by following the <HI>Directions</HI> and Precepts of the <HI>Antients,</HI> who knew little or nothing of the unaccountable <HI>Mixtures, Complications</HI> and <HI>Di&s;gui&s;es,</HI> which we daily &s;ee; and yet &s;ome are &s;o &s;otti&s;h to confine them&s;elves to &s;uch &s;uperannuated exploded <HI>Definitions, Notions</HI> and <HI>Medicines</HI> as they have left us, who pra|cti&s;ed when Di&s;ea&s;es were but <HI>few,</HI> more <HI>&s;ingle, calm</HI> and <HI>gentle,</HI> and more tractable and <HI>curable</HI> than at this Day, when its rare to &s;ind an <HI>uncomplicated</HI> Di&s;ea&s;e, in which the Blood and other Humours are not <HI>viti|ated,</HI> by being unhappily mix'd with other un&s;een Maladies.</P>
<P>Now becau&s;e the <HI>Scurvy</HI> is a lurking Di&s;|ea&s;e, and con&s;umes the Patient by in&s;en&s;ible or &s;low degrees, and its direful effects are never &s;o much perceived or felt, as when it intermixes it &s;elf with other Di&s;ea&s;es, &s;o its &s;eldom regarded as the principal Offender, but the the Di&s;ea&s;e is chiefly attributed to the Concommitant Di&s;temper that cau&s;es Pain. So it often happens, that a continued latent <HI>Scurvy</HI> is little ob&s;erved, but when its joined with the Cholick that cau&s;es griping tormenting Pains, the Di&s;ea&s;e is called a <HI>Cholick,</HI>
<PB N="53" REF="54">and Remedies u&s;ed accordingly without Suc|ce&s;s, becau&s;e the <HI>Scurvy</HI> was neglected, tho' &s;carce any effect requires a more &s;peedy <HI>Phy&s;ical</HI> help, than the <HI>Cholick</HI> and Gripes of the Be&s;ly occa&s;ion'd by the <HI>Scurvy,</HI> which makes them more violent, and of longer continuance, by ob&s;tinately re&s;i&s;ting the Methods of Cure.</P>
<P>In the Symptoms of the <HI>Scorbutick Cholick,</HI><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms of the Scorbutick Cholick.</NOTE> I &s;hall be very brief, having been very large on that Head in the foregoing Cholicks.</P>
<P>The u&s;ual Signs are, high colour'd Urine or precipitating a Red Sandy Fle&s;h colour'd Sediment, or fa&s;tens red friable Sand upon the &s;ides of the Urinal. Continual Pain of the <HI>Head, Palpitation</HI> of the Heart, <HI>puffing</HI> up of the Stomach, <HI>loathing,</HI> Vomiting, Belching, Hiccough, Cough, Tumors and <HI>Putrefaction</HI> of the <HI>Gums</HI> with much Spitting; Loo&s;ene&s;s and <HI>blackne&s;s</HI> of the Teeth, (for the Cure of which I have a Dentefrice which makes the Teeth as White as Ivory,) the <HI>Breath</HI> &s;tinks, and is &s;ometimes fetch'd with great <HI>difficulty,</HI> and is &s;eldom free from terrible Pains of the <HI>Cholick,</HI> and trembling and loo&s;ene&s;s of the <HI>Joints</HI> and Limbs, with <HI>Lazine&s;s</HI> and often <HI>Faint Sweats;</HI> there is al&s;o &s;ometimes Malignant <HI>&V;lcers,</HI> dry hard <HI>Tubercles, Eri&s;ipelas,</HI> and <HI>Oedematous</HI> Tumors, with many others, which to enumerate, were to comprehend an univer&s;al Genus of <HI>Atoms</HI> within a very narrow Limitation.</P>
<P>This Di&s;ea&s;e is very <HI>hard</HI> to cure, where the Scorbutick Humour is obdurate and <HI>pre|dominant,</HI> and when the Cure has been too long <HI>delayed,</HI> or not treated as a <HI>complicated</HI> Di&s;ea&s;e, many times 'tis very <HI>Dangerous,</HI> the Pains of the <HI>Cholick</HI> may run into an incurable
<PB N="54" REF="55"><HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> and its &s;ullen Companion, may bring a <HI>Drop&s;ie,</HI> a <HI>Con&s;umption,</HI> or other Mor|tal <HI>Chronical</HI> Di&s;tempers, and &s;ometimes <HI>Acute</HI> Di&s;ea&s;es, as the <HI>Appoplexy Swooning,</HI> or the like; which produce &s;udden Death.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of a Scorbu|tick Cho|lick.</NOTE>The <HI>Immediate cau&s;es</HI> of this Di&s;ea&s;e, is, a volatile <HI>Acid,</HI> that irritates the <HI>Nerves</HI> and <HI>Membranes,</HI> &s;harpens the <HI>Lympha,</HI> debauches the innate <HI>Spirits</HI> of the Parts, and perverts the <HI>equal</HI> temperature of the Blood. The <HI>Remote Cau&s;es,</HI> are, <HI>Sea Air</HI> impregnated with <HI>Salin,</HI> Acid Vapours, <HI>Salt</HI> and Vi&s;cous Food, <HI>Lazine&s;s,</HI> Weakne&s;s of <HI>Dige&s;tion,</HI> Infection, a <HI>Hereditary</HI> Conveyance, and the <HI>influence</HI> of Chronical Di&s;ea&s;es. If the Di&s;ea&s;e is <HI>recent</HI> it admits of Cure. If <HI>inveterate,</HI> it requires a continued u&s;e of proper Medicines for a long &s;pace of time.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cure of a Scorbutick Cholick.</NOTE>The Cure of a <HI>Scorbutick Cholick,</HI> con&s;i&s;ts, in correcting and evacuating the <HI>Crudities</HI> of the fir&s;t Pa&s;&s;ages, fortifying the <HI>Stomach,</HI> re|trieving the due <HI>Cra&s;is</HI> of the Blood, re&s;toring all wonted <HI>Evacuations</HI> to their former Cour&s;e, and to appea&s;e excruciating Pains. In order then to compa&s;s the&s;e Ends, and Cure this &s;tubborn and rebellious Di&s;ea&s;e, the Sick mu&s;t ob&s;erve a good <HI>Diet,</HI> without which Phy&s;ical means will profit but little: And here, becau&s;e in the fir&s;t place there will be a nece&s;&s;ity (if po&s;&s;ible) to give <HI>Ea&s;e</HI> in the Fit by <HI>Opiates,</HI> let them always be ac|companied by <HI>Anti&s;corbutick Specificks,</HI> of which may be prepared diver&s;ity of good Medicines, both <HI>Chymical</HI> and <HI>Galenical.</HI> The <HI>Volatile Salts</HI> both of Animals and Vegitables are excellent to open all Ob&s;tructions, and Temper the Humours; al&s;o, <HI>Elixir Proprie|tatis,</HI> the Spirit of <HI>Sal Armoniack,</HI> the Spirit
<PB N="55" REF="56">of <HI>Nitre,</HI> and of <HI>Salt</HI> Dulcified, <HI>Salt of Steel, Wormwood</HI> and <HI>Tartar, Oil of Juniper, Cloves</HI> and <HI>Cinamon,</HI> are all Anti&s;corbutick Spe|cificks.</P>
<P>Next in order are gentle <HI>Laxitives,</HI> e&s;pe|cially in Hot Con&s;titutions; &s;uch are Pills of <HI>Armoniacum,</HI> or tho&s;e of <HI>Tartar</HI> mix'd with &s;weet <HI>Mercury,</HI> to prevent or take a|way Co&s;tivene&s;s. <HI>Re&s;inous</HI> Purgatives are to be avoided, as beings endow'd with an <HI>A|&s;tringent</HI> Quality. <HI>Rai&s;ins, Prunes, Tamarinds,</HI> and Ripe &s;weet <HI>Apples,</HI> or their expre&s;s'd <HI>Juice</HI> are of con&s;iderable Efficacy in this Ca&s;e; but <HI>Sugar</HI> and other &s;weet things ought to be carefully avoided. <HI>Rhubarb</HI> or <HI>Cream of Tartar,</HI> &s;harpened with Pouder of <HI>Jalap,</HI> are proper for &s;uch as are of a <HI>Moi&s;t</HI> Juicy Con|&s;titution.</P>
<P>The Patient's Body being thus prepared, you ought to proceed to <HI>Alteratives,</HI> &s;uch are <HI>Steel</HI> and all fix'd <HI>Salts,</HI> or whatever &s;ubdues an <HI>Acid.</HI> To which join <HI>Aperient, Diureticks</HI> and <HI>bitter</HI> Stomachical <HI>Aromaticks,</HI> or the Spirituous Volatile <HI>Salts, Myn&s;ichts Arcan&umacr;m Duplicatum,</HI> is of excellent u&s;e, e&s;pecially when the Sick is troubled with <HI>Flu&s;hings</HI> and &s;udden Inflamations. <HI>Elixir Proprietatis</HI> pre|pared with an <HI>Acid</HI> and mix'd with the Spi|rit of <HI>Scurvigra&s;s,</HI> and that of <HI>Sal Armoniac</HI> is al&s;o proper. The Tincture of <HI>Tartar</HI> mix'd with the Spirit of <HI>Sal-Armoniack,</HI> and given by degrees to Forty Drops, is a celebrated Medicine. And as you find occa&s;ion, Fo|mentations, Ligatures, Vento&s;es, Sternuta|tories, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> are of u&s;e.</P>
<P>I have been long you &s;ee in di&s;cour&s;ing the Cure of the <HI>Scorbutick Cholick,</HI> according to the general Method of Practice, becau&s;e its
<PB N="56" REF="57">a &s;tubborn Di&s;ea&s;e, and too often of <HI>long</HI> continuance: Occa&s;ion'd by this Di&s;ea&s;e, being, as it were, an odd and <HI>new</HI> kind of Di&s;temper, not reducible to the old <HI>Cla&s;s</HI> of Cholicks. Secondly being not con&s;ider'd in its various <HI>Mixtures, Complications</HI> and <HI>Di&s;|gui&s;es,</HI> which requires other &s;orts of Medi|cines to cure it, than are commonly pre|&s;cribed. Thirdly by Practioners being con|founded by variety of Medicines directed by Authors, who &s;eeing one Medicine <HI>fail,</HI> run to another, and &s;o from Medicine to Medicine in an endle&s;s Circuit, till they have either de&s;troy'd or nau&s;eated their Pa|tients, as well as cram'd their <HI>Chamber</HI>-Windows and <HI>Tables,</HI> with Galipots, Gla&s;&s;es, Boxes and Papers, who&s;e Contents, in&s;tead of expelling noxious Humours, had no other effect than draining the Patient's <HI>Pur&s;e</HI> to enrich an unexperienc'd, unskilfull Phy|&s;ician.</P>
<P>Now the&s;e Evils, almo&s;t grown a common Nu&s;ance to the Publick, as well as a Re|proach to Phy&s;itians, are remedied, by tho&s;e few Men, of which number, I profe&s;s my &s;elf to be One, that make <HI>Art</HI> follow <HI>Na|ture,</HI> rather than &s;train <HI>Nature</HI> and her <HI>Ano|malies</HI> to general Rules of <HI>Art,</HI> and who &s;ee|ing <HI>Nature</HI> degenerated into Extravagancies and <HI>complicated</HI> Di&s;ea&s;es, unknown to the <HI>Ancients,</HI> endeavour to find out <HI>Experienc'd</HI> ways to deal with her, however various and di&s;gui&s;ed, and by red cing a whole <HI>Apothe|cary</HI>'s Shop into a few well &s;tudied and often Experienc'd Medicines; &s;uch Men tho' fal&s;ely called <HI>Empericks,</HI> will be <HI>Ma&s;ters</HI> in the Art of <HI>Phy&s;ick</HI> &s;ince they can truly &s;ay with <HI>Ovid</HI> Remed. Am. l. 2.</P>
<PB N="57" REF="58">
<Q><P>Et quoniam vaniant Morbi, variabimus Artes Mille Mali &s;pecies, Mille &s;alutis erunt.</P>
<L>Becau&s;e Di&s;ea&s;es mix and vary, therefore we</L>
<L>Do vary Arts of Cure; and tho' there be</L>
<L>A Thou&s;and &s;orts of &s;trange Di&s;tempers &s;teal</L>
<L>On us, we have mo&s;t certain ways to heal.</L></Q>
<P>This being the main and <HI>hone&s;t</HI> de&s;ign of Practi&s;ing, it will be no &s;trange thing to be|lieve, that I being bred an <HI>Apothecary</HI> and ha|ving &s;een the <HI>ineffectual</HI> Pre&s;cription and mul|tiplicity of Medicines u&s;ed by other Men, and dedicating my Life to the Service of Mankind, in the Knowledge and Practice of <HI>Phy&s;ick,</HI> that I &s;hould by <HI>Conver&s;ation,</HI> much reading of the be&s;t Authors, <HI>Foreign</HI> and <HI>Dome&s;tick,</HI> and by almo&s;t a Twenty Years Practice, be able to &s;horten the <HI>number</HI> of Medicines and contract them into a <HI>few;</HI> but &s;o efficacious in their <HI>Nature</HI> and <HI>Effects,</HI> as render them effectual in mo&s;t Di&s;ea&s;es, and &s;uch I a&s;&s;ure you I have for the Cure of this <HI>Contumacious</HI> Di&s;ea&s;e, the <HI>Scorbutick Cho|lick;</HI> of which I could give you numerous Examples of Per&s;ons cured by them, as well as in the&s;e few, that follow, who have given me leave to make u&s;e of their Names, and Places of Abode: Of which I &s;ee I mu&s;t be more &s;paring for the future, becau&s;e the Book begins to &s;well into a larger Volume than I fir&s;t intended.</P>
<P><HI>Elizabeth</HI> the late Wife of <HI>Robert Miles,</HI> Tobacconi&s;t, in <HI>Lamb-Alley,</HI> in <HI>Abchurch-Lane,</HI> was for &s;ome Years troubled with a Complication of Di&s;ea&s;es, <HI>viz.</HI> the <HI>Scorbutick
<PB N="58" REF="59">Cholick, Rheumati&s;m, Sciatica, Pal&s;ey, Gravil in the Kidneys,</HI> and very trouble&s;ome <HI>Vapours,</HI> living in &s;o mi&s;erable a Condition, that &s;he was left off by &s;everal Practioners as <HI>Incure|able,</HI> and thought to be even at the very <HI>Brink</HI> of the <HI>Grave;</HI> but being committed to my Gare, thro' the ble&s;&s;ing of God upon the u&s;e of my Medicines, I cured her of her complicated Di&s;tempers to that Degree, that &s;he comfortably attends her daily Af|fairs, and enjoys a <HI>better</HI> &s;tate of Health that &s;he had done for <HI>Six Years</HI> la&s;t pa&s;t. The truth whereof &s;he is ready and willing to atte&s;t upon <HI>Oath</HI> before a Magi&s;trate, as &s;he has done to me in a Certificate under her Hand.</P>
<P>Mr. <HI>William Bagley,</HI> Cloth-Worker, i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Miles</HI>'s-<HI>Alley,</HI> in <HI>Petticoat-Lane,</HI> was afflicte<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> with a <HI>Rhuemati&s;m,</HI> complicated with <HI>Scor|butick Cholick</HI> Pains, for Four Years &s;ucce&s;|&s;ively at <HI>Spring</HI> and <HI>Fall;</HI> a lamene&s;s in hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Hands and Feet, with large <HI>Knobs</HI> and Swel|lings, was cured by the u&s;e of my Medi|cines, and has continued in firm Health without any Symptoms of a <HI>Relaps,</HI> or the <HI>return</HI> of Pain for a long &s;pace of time, as h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> will &s;atisfy any Per&s;on that enquires <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 word"> him.</P>
<P><HI>William We&s;t</HI> Senior, Waterman, dwellin<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> near St. <HI>Saviour</HI>'s-<HI>Mill-Stairs,</HI> in <HI>Southwar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> was violently afflicted with a <HI>Scorbutick Cho|lick,</HI> joined with <HI>Nephritick</HI> Pains, vulgarl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> called the <HI>Stone Cholick,</HI> and receiving <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 word"> help from others, addre&s;s'd him&s;elf to m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters"> and I at a <HI>&s;mall</HI> charge, and in <HI>little</HI> tim<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> ca&s;ed him of his terrible griping Pains, ar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">
<PB N="59" REF="60">brought away Three large <HI>Stones.</HI> In grati|tude for which Cure, he recommended &s;e|veral of his Neighbours to me, who were troubled with the like Di&s;ea&s;e, who <HI>all,</HI> as well as him&s;elf were cured, to their great &s;atisfaction.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion.</NOTE>I his Di&s;ea&s;e called in Greek <GAP DESC="foreign"> in Latin <HI>Iliaca Pa&s;&s;io,</HI> from the Gut <HI>Ileon,</HI> which is chiefly affected in this Di&s;temper, is a <HI>Cholick in exce&s;s,</HI> an extream <HI>Co&s;tivene&s;s,</HI> pain about the <HI>Navel,</HI> ri&s;ing from the inverted <HI>Peri&s;taltick</HI> motion of the <HI>Guts,</HI> di&s;gorging the Excrements upward; for the <HI>Fibres</HI> of the <HI>Guts</HI> which ought to be <HI>contracted</HI> from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">e Superior towards the Inferior, are drawn to the Superior; &s;o what&s;oever is contained in the Guts is Vomited up, and <HI>Cly&s;ters</HI> how &s;harp &s;o ever become Vomitive: <HI>Purges</HI> al&s;o taken by the Mouth are ca&s;t up by <HI>Vomit;</HI> and I am of Opinion, that the exqui&s;ite and intollerable <HI>Pain</HI> coming upon this Di&s;ea&s;e, is only occa&s;ion'd by the afore&s;aid <HI>Prepo&s;terous</HI> motions of the Guts; for as tho&s;e <HI>Folds</HI> which the many Circumvolutions of the Guts make, are &s;o formed by Nature, that they &s;hould mo&s;t aptly conduce to the car|rying, down of the <HI>Feces;</HI> when they are forced to give way to a motion <HI>contrary</HI> to their <HI>Fibres,</HI> the afore&s;aid Pain is occa&s;ion'd from thence, which is fix'd to one <HI>Part,</HI> and is like the boaring of an <HI>Augur,</HI> when ei|ther the <HI>value,</HI> which is &s;eated at the be|ginning of the <HI>Colon,</HI> hinders the going <HI>back</HI> of the Excrements to the <HI>Ilium,</HI> or any o|ther <HI>Membrane</HI> belonging to the <HI>Sinus,</HI> &s;u&s;tains alone the force of this <HI>Peri&s;taltick</HI> motion.</P>
<PB N="60" REF="61">
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms of an Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion.</NOTE>The Signs of an approaching <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> are, extream <HI>Co&s;tivene&s;s,</HI> retraction of the <HI>Anus,</HI> a Loathing, Vomiting and <HI>intollerable</HI> Pains in the &s;mall Guts; and if a <HI>Hiccough</HI> follow it, threatens Death. If the <HI>Anus</HI> is much drawn back, &s;o that a <HI>Cly&s;ter-Pipe</HI> can|not enter it, 'tis a &s;ign that the gro&s;s In|testiness are affected. If otherwi&s;e the &s;mall Guts are touched. If the greate&s;t Pain po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es the <HI>Epiga&s;trium,</HI> the <HI>Ilium</HI> is mo&s;t oppre&s;s'd. A &s;hooting burning Pain in one particular part of the Body, a <HI>Lipyria</HI> Fever. If the Pain <HI>cea&s;ing</HI> is attended by cold <HI>Sweats, difficult Re&s;piration, Swoonings,</HI> and &s;ometimes <HI>Convul&s;ions,</HI> 'tis a Sign of a <HI>Gangrene,</HI> cau&s;ed by the <HI>corrugation</HI> of the Guts, mi&s;taken by &s;ome for a <HI>twi&s;ting</HI> of 'em round one another, a thing <HI>incon&s;i&s;tent</HI> with their <HI>Ligation</HI> to the <HI>Me&s;entery.</HI> In fine, the common Symptoms of an <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> are hardne&s;s of the <HI>Belly,</HI> &s;uppre&s;&s;ion of the <HI>&V;rine,</HI> Loathing, <HI>Vomiting,</HI> fir&s;t the <HI>contents</HI> of the Stomach, and next the <HI>Excrements,</HI> a &s;tinking <HI>habit</HI> of Body, fre|quent <HI>Swoonings,</HI> in&s;ufferable griping <HI>Pains</HI> in the Guts, a prodigious <HI>Anxiety,</HI> and &s;ome|times Vomiting of <HI>Cly&s;ters.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Progno|&s;tick Signs.</NOTE>In the Progno&s;ticks of an <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">n|flamations</HI> or <HI>Gangreenes</HI> are Mortal. If the upper Gut <HI>de&s;cend</HI> in the lower 'tis a <HI>fatal</HI> Symptom. If the lower <HI>a&s;cend</HI> into the higher, 'tis <HI>curable.</HI> If the Di&s;ea&s;e proceed from a <HI>Rupture</HI> or hardened Excrements, 'tis not de&s;perate. If Sleep &s;ucceeds the taking of <HI>Opiates,</HI> 'tis a <HI>hopeful</HI> Indication. <HI>Deafne&s;s</HI> or <HI>Dotings</HI> are pernicious con&s;equences. If the Sweat, Breath, and Belching <HI>&s;tink</HI> very much, <HI>Death</HI> is about to put an <HI>End</HI> to the Patient's Mi&s;ery.</P>
<PB N="61" REF="62">
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of the Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion.</NOTE>The Cau&s;e of an <HI>Ileos,</HI> or <HI>Iliaca Pa&s;&s;io,</HI> is a excrementitious <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> Matter, adhering to the Gut <HI>Ileo,</HI> which in time is coagulated into a very hard &s;ub&s;tance, almo&s;t in the Form of <HI>Bullets,</HI> whence all the <HI>pa&s;&s;age</HI> for Excrements by &s;iege is &s;top'd, and anon their <HI>regre&s;s</HI> and <HI>a&s;cent</HI> to the Stomach fol|lows, with a mi&s;erable Vomiting of them up.</P>
<P>The Rupture of the <HI>Peritoneum</HI> may cau&s;e this grievous Di&s;ea&s;e, e&s;pecially if it be &s;o great, that not only the &s;mall Guts but the great ones al&s;o, fall through the <HI>lacerated</HI> Orifice, and renders them uncapable of be|ing <HI>reduced</HI> or put back through the &s;ame <HI>Hole;</HI> &s;o that a hard and un&s;upportable <HI>Tu|mor</HI> follows, which hinders the <HI>Reflux</HI> of Blood, and cau&s;es an <HI>Inflamation,</HI> and con|&s;equently a <HI>Gangrene</HI> in the Guts, attended with a violent Vomiting of the Excrements and a &s;peedy &s;ummons to the Grave.</P>
<P>But we may chiefly a&s;&s;ign a twofold Cau&s;e of this <HI>Inver&s;ion,</HI> from whence the Pain ari&s;es, and they are <HI>Ob&s;truction</HI> and <HI>Irritation;</HI> for whatever violently ob&s;tructs the <HI>Inte&s;tines,</HI> &s;o that nothing can pa&s;s <HI>downwards,</HI> nece&s;&s;a|rily occa&s;ions this <HI>contrary</HI> Motion in them, as hardned Excrements, gro&s;s Wind col|lected in great quantity, <HI>&amp;c. Irritation</HI> pro|ceeds from &s;harp and <HI>Malignant</HI> Humours ca&s;t upon the Stomach and Guts that are next to it, by the exce&s;&s;ive raging of the Blood, by rea&s;on of a late <HI>Fever</HI> begun, whereby the <HI>motion</HI> of the Stomach is fir&s;t <HI>Inverted,</HI> and violently forced to ca&s;t up what is contained in it; at length the &s;mall Guts that are joined to the Stomach being weakned, yield to the <HI>violent</HI> Motion of it,
<PB N="62" REF="63">and with them at la&s;t the <HI>greater</HI> follow by con&s;ent; the Stomach Vomiting beginning the fatal Tragedy: And this may be truly call'd the <HI>Iliack</HI> Pa&s;&s;ion.</P>
<P>The cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, con&s;i&s;ts in re|moving the <HI>Irritation,</HI> and retrieving the <HI>Natural</HI> Motion of the Guts, to that end if the Excrements are harden'd they ought to be &s;often'd by the &s;peedy exhibition of <HI>Cly&s;ters,</HI> before they are hardened beyond Re|lief. All Purgatives are improper, till the Pain in the <HI>Guts</HI> and <HI>Stomach</HI> are quieted, and re&s;tored to their Natural Motion, which you may know, by a large quantity of Hu|mours being voided <HI>downwards</HI> by the help of <HI>Nature</HI> or <HI>Art. Opiates</HI> are very hurtful in ca&s;e of a <HI>Gangrene</HI> and in that of <HI>Ob&s;tructions,</HI> till the Belly is well opened; but if the Di&s;|ea&s;e proceed from violent <HI>Irritations,</HI> attend|ed by continual <HI>vomiting, Opiates</HI> may be mix'd with <HI>Stomachical</HI> Medicines while the Patient is &s;trong: Always remembring, that what|ever you u&s;e in the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, whether <HI>outwardly</HI> or <HI>inwardly,</HI> mu&s;t be <HI>Warm,</HI> both in the Fit, and when the Patient is on the mending hand.</P>
<P>If the <HI>Small Guts</HI> only are inverted, give Emollient Cly&s;ters, quickned with <HI>Sal Gem,</HI> or the Infu&s;ion of <HI>Crocus Metallorum,</HI> or tho&s;e of the <HI>Carminative Seeds</HI> boiled in Childs Urine and Water: But if the <HI>great</HI> ones are al&s;o Inverted, that &s;ort of Cly&s;ters are <HI>noxious,</HI> and you mu&s;t &s;eek help from <HI>tem|perate,</HI> Laxative, lubrical Potions; &s;uch as the Decoction of <HI>Emollient</HI> Herbs in Broath, mix'd with <HI>Oil</HI> of <HI>Sweet Almonds</HI> newly drawn.</P>
<PB N="63" REF="64">
<P>When all other Medicines want Succe&s;s, &s;ome Men give <HI>Leaden Bullets,</HI> and boa&s;t of the u&s;e of <HI>Quick&s;ilver,</HI> which I have &s;eldom known to have done much good, but often prove injurious, e&s;pecially in an <HI>Inflamation, Rupture, Gangrene,</HI> or <HI>falling of the upper Gut into the lower;</HI> therefore if any Practitioner thinks him&s;elf under a nece&s;&s;ity of u&s;ing <HI>Quick&s;ilver,</HI> which is prefered before <HI>Bullets,</HI> let him be &s;ure to prepare his Patient's Body before he gives it, with <HI>lubric al</HI> Medi|cines, &s;uch as <HI>Oil</HI> of <HI>Sweet Almonds</HI> new drawn, or <HI>Sperma Caeti:</HI> Then exhibit Three, Four, and &s;ometimes Eight <HI>Ounces</HI> of purified <HI>Quick&s;ilver,</HI> together with Oil of <HI>Sweet Al|monds</HI> and <HI>Mint Water;</HI> and if it does not an&s;wer his Intentions at fir&s;t, let it be fre|quently repeated, and the mean while inject Emollient Cly&s;ters, foment the Belly with <HI>&s;oftning</HI> Decoctions; or &s;et the Sick into a pro|per <HI>Bath.</HI> If the <HI>Mercury</HI> does not force its way out of the Body, give &s;harp <HI>Cly&s;ters,</HI> and anoint the Belly with Oil of <HI>Coloquintida</HI> to &s;often the Excrements. If the <HI>Quick&s;ilver</HI> offend the Mouth, Throat and Gums, check its <HI>virulence</HI> with a Gargari&s;m of <HI>Honey of Ro&s;es,</HI> and <HI>Syrup of Violets;</HI> and if the <HI>Mercury</HI> is &s;ucce&s;sful in opening the Body, remember to exhibit the <HI>Lunar Bezoar</HI> and <HI>Diaphoretick Antimony,</HI> to expel the remains of the <HI>Mer|cury;</HI> for tho' <HI>Mercury</HI> given by an <HI>Intelligent</HI> Per&s;on is an <HI>Excellent</HI> Medicine, yet it always does <HI>Mi&s;chief,</HI> if any of it &s;tays too long in the Body.</P>
<P>The&s;e are the u&s;ual Methods for di&s;co|vering the Cau&s;e and curing this Di&s;ea&s;e, which I publi&s;h in this &s;uccinct way; Fir&s;t, to a&s;&s;i&s;t tho&s;e that want greater <HI>Light;</HI> Se|condly
<PB N="64" REF="65">to &s;hew, that I am thoroughly in|&s;tructed in the <HI>Knowledge</HI> of Phy&s;ick; and, Thirdly, to <HI>&s;ilence</HI> Malicious <HI>Back-biters,</HI> who for want of <HI>bu&s;ine&s;s,</HI> make it part of their employment, to repre&s;ent me in their ow<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Cla&s;s of <HI>Ignoramus</HI>'s which this <HI>Treati&s;e,</HI> a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters"> the re&s;t that are to follow it, will plainly <HI>confute,</HI> in the Opinion of all Men of Sen&s;e, Genero&s;ity and Learning.</P>
<P>In my own Practice for the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, when it evidently appears by the Symptoms above-named, and by Vomiting up <HI>Cly&s;ters,</HI> that its a true <HI>Iliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> I apply my &s;elf to give the Patient &s;ome Ea&s;e, if it be po&s;&s;ible; for let others &s;ay what they plea&s;e, he that can do that has half <HI>conquer'd</HI> the Di&s;ea&s;e, for then Nature will a&s;&s;i&s;t in removing the Cau&s;e, by being <HI>enabled</HI> to &s;u&s;tain the <HI>Force</HI> of Medicines proper to &s;often the Excrements, and after to expel them by Siege: And to this end, I give my <HI>Elixir</HI> in &s;mall Do&s;es, repeat them often, and enlarge the number of Drops every time they are given, and I never found them un&s;ucce&s;sful; their Vertue being to <HI>invigorate</HI> the Sick by giving him a relaxation from his Pain, Mollifying the offending Matter, and by that means preparing and &s;moothing the way for my <HI>Pills to drive it out</HI> by gentle degrees; for this Di&s;ea&s;e will endure no rough and violent Treatment.</P>
<P>Here I cannot, according to Cu&s;tom, give <HI>Examples</HI> of Per&s;ons Cured by the u&s;e of my <HI>Two above-named Remedies;</HI> (one I cured &s;ome|time &s;ince, but am not permitted to make u&s;e of her Name,) for tho', ble&s;&s;ed be God, I have never <HI>wanted</HI> Succe&s;s, yet I could
<PB N="65" REF="66">not prevail with the Patients I have Cured, to give me leave to Name them, and &s;o the <HI>Credit</HI> of my Medicines in this Ca&s;e, can have no other <HI>Vouchers</HI> but my own <HI>Word</HI> and <HI>Reputation,</HI> which I value my &s;elf more upon than Ten Thou&s;and <HI>Te&s;timonials.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Cae|liack Cho|lick.</NOTE>Called in Greek <GAP DESC="foreign">, in Latin <HI>Caeliaca Pa&s;&s;io,</HI> the <HI>Caeliack Pa&s;&s;ion,</HI> or <HI>Caeliack Cholick,</HI> is a <HI>Loo&s;ene&s;s</HI> of the Belly, when the Meat comes forth <HI>crude</HI> and imperfectly dige&s;ted; which &s;ome &s;ay is not to be refered to the <HI>Concoction</HI> only being hurt, but to the debility of the <HI>Retentive</HI> Faculty, the Food being not long enough <HI>retained</HI> to be Concocted; by which it appears, &s;ay they, that the Di&s;ea&s;e proceeds from a <HI>fault</HI> in the Stomach as well as in the <HI>Guts:</HI> But the Learned <HI>Etmullerus,</HI> &s;ays, it is a <HI>Flux</HI> of the <HI>Belly,</HI> by which the <HI>Chyle</HI> is voided together with Excrements, the Stomach being in <HI>no fault,</HI> becau&s;e <HI>Chy|lification</HI> is duly perform'd there; therefore the blame, &s;ays he, mu&s;t either be laid on the <HI>Bile,</HI> that is &s;topt in its Pa&s;&s;age to the Guts, or by degenerating from its <HI>Saline</HI> Acrimony, and con&s;equently is unfit to &s;e|perate the <HI>Chyle:</HI> Or el&s;e on the <HI>Lacteal</HI> Ve&s;&s;els through which the <HI>Chyle</HI> ought to pa&s;s, their <HI>Orifices</HI> being covered With <HI>Slime,</HI> or &s;hut by the <HI>Contraction,</HI> or <HI>Corro&s;ion</HI> of the Inte&s;tines occa&s;ion'd by <HI>Fluxes.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms of a Cae|liaca.</NOTE>The <HI>Symptoms</HI> of this Di&s;ea&s;e, are, extra|or<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">inary, Pains both in the upper and lower <HI>Region</HI> of the Belly, not unattended with Pain in the Back and Limbs; for all compli|cated Di&s;ea&s;es, generally affect all the Neigh|bouring Parts, as well as the Place where they are more particularly and chiefly &s;eat|ed;
<PB N="66" REF="67">and that you may have a true notion of this Maladay, ob&s;erve, that if the <HI>Bile</HI> is defective, the Excrements are <HI>White,</HI> or very <HI>Pale;</HI> without any &s;ign of &s;eparation. If the ob&s;truction of the <HI>Lacteal</HI> Veins cau&s;e the Di&s;ea&s;e, the Excrements are <HI>Yellowi&s;h,</HI> and the <HI>Chyle,</HI> tho' voided at the &s;ame time with them, is but <HI>loo&s;ely</HI> mix'd with them, as being <HI>&s;eparated</HI> in the Guts, but <HI>di&s;appointed</HI> in its Pa&s;&s;age.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of a Coaliack Cholick.</NOTE>The Cau&s;es of this Di&s;temper, are gene|rally rank'd under Three Heads, which will comprehend all the differing Opinions about it. The Fir&s;t is a <HI>Cold</HI> Di&s;temper of the <HI>Sto|mach</HI> and <HI>Liver,</HI> which generate <HI>Phlegmatick</HI> and <HI>Glutinous</HI> Humours, which cover the <HI>Wrincles</HI> of the Stomach that it cannot <HI>retain</HI> the <HI>Food:</HI> Tho' Retention be made by the <HI>A&s;tringing</HI> Quality, yet it operates by fit In|&s;truments, <HI>viz.</HI> the <HI>rawne&s;s</HI> of the <HI>Inward</HI> Coat of the Stomach; which rawne&s;s being taken away, and the Wrincles filled by the Humours afore&s;aid, the <HI>Retention</HI> is damni|fied, and the Food <HI>Slips</HI> away without <HI>Con|coction.</HI></P>
<P>The Second Cau&s;e a&s;&s;igned by others, is, violent <HI>&s;harp</HI> Humours, that prick, twinge, and irritate the Parts, by which the Sto|mach and Guts are <HI>provoked</HI> to &s;end out the Meat too &s;oon.</P>
<P>The Third, and which I take to be the true Cau&s;e of the <HI>Caeliack Cholick,</HI> is, the Ob&s;truction of the <HI>Me&s;enteraick</HI> Veins which hinder the pa&s;&s;age of the <HI>Chyle</HI> to the <HI>Liver,</HI> or the Ob&s;truction of the <HI>Glandules</HI> of the <HI>Me&s;entery,</HI> and therefore mu&s;t of nece&s;&s;ity be ejected by the Belly. If this: Di&s;ea&s;e is of <HI>long</HI> continuance 'tis very dangerous, be|cau&s;e
<PB N="67" REF="68">Nature is <HI>deprived</HI> of her Nouri&s;hment, and the Weak Body is liable to the <HI>In&s;ults</HI> of all Di&s;ea&s;es.</P>
<P>Now, &s;ince the Di&s;ea&s;e called <GAP DESC="foreign">, a <HI>Lientary,</HI> is al&s;o a <HI>Flux</HI> of the Belly, in which the <HI>Food</HI> is quickly thrown out of the Body <HI>undige&s;ted;</HI> and differs only from a <HI>Caeliack Cholick</HI> in <HI>degrees,</HI> and that their <HI>Cures</HI> are the <HI>&s;ame;</HI> I &s;hall omit treating particu|larly on that Head, and refer the Reader to what follows.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cure of the Caelick Cholick.</NOTE>The <HI>Curatory</HI> Indication of the <HI>Caeliack Choliack,</HI> is, to remove the <HI>Morbi&s;ick</HI> Cau&s;e, and &s;trengthen the <HI>Stomach,</HI> which kind of Method being &s;ea&s;onably begun, and duly pro&s;ecuted often does the whole Work; for the <HI>Cau&s;e</HI> of the Di&s;ea&s;e or the <HI>Root</HI> of it being cut off, the <HI>Effects</HI> depending on it, die of their own accord. Therefore if the <HI>Bile</HI> is &s;luggi&s;h, or &s;topp'd in its Pa&s;&s;age, means mu&s;t be u&s;ed to make it more <HI>Active,</HI> to correct the <HI>Acid</HI> and Au&s;ture <HI>Ferment</HI> pro|ceeding from the Stomach and Inte&s;tines, to retrieve the Natual <HI>Texture</HI> and di&s;tribu|tion of the <HI>Bile</HI> and to promote the <HI>Separation</HI> of the Heterogenious <HI>Particles.</HI> If the <HI>Lacteal</HI> or Milky Ve&s;&s;els are &s;hut up, endeavour to remove the <HI>Slime</HI> that choaks them, by at|tenuating, opening Ingredients, <HI>A&s;tringents</HI> are improper. Let the Peccant humours be <HI>purged:</HI> After which the Tincture of <HI>Tartar,</HI> or of the <HI>Dro&s;s of Regules of Antimony,</HI> or <HI>Chalybeate Tinctures, mix'd with the Spirit of Sal Armoniaci,</HI> are very convenient to &s;trengthen the Stomach by procuring an Appetite. <HI>Amatus Lu&s;itanus</HI> highly commends the following Pre&s;cription. <HI>Con&s;erve of Ro&s;es &s;ix Ounces, Venice Treacle &s;ix Drams, and Syrup
<PB N="68" REF="69">of Quinces a &s;ufficient quantity to make an Opiate:</HI> Halt an Ounce of which mu&s;t be taken in the Morning, fa&s;ting an Hour after it.</P>
<P>For the U&s;e and Benefit of my own Pa|tients, I have &s;tated and well experienc'd Medicines for the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 word"> which I could give numerous Examples, tho' I only prodnce Two.</P>
<Q><L>Experience guides my Practice; others may do,</L>
<L>What their Inclinations prompt them to.</L></Q>
<P>Mrs. <HI>Anne Percival,</HI> of <HI>Ru&s;&s;el-&s;treet Blooms|bury,</HI> was for &s;everal Years grieved with a <HI>Caeliack Cholick</HI> at certain Times and Sea&s;ons only, but about Three Months &s;ince, &s;he was &s;eized with it in &s;o <HI>violent</HI> and terrible a manner, that her <HI>Life</HI> was de&s;pair'd of: And having by the Advice of &s;ome able Phy&s;icians, taken divers Medicines, with|out receiving any Benefit by them; at length hearing of my great &s;ucce&s;s in curing the <HI>Cholick,</HI> of what kind &s;oever; &s;he came to me, who thro' the Divine Ble&s;&s;ing, and the u&s;e of my <HI>Medicines,</HI> was cured in a &s;hort Time. And that others who &s;uffer the like <HI>cruel</HI> Pains, and <HI>langui&s;h</HI> under that Di&s;ea&s;e, might al&s;o find Relief, gave me Authority under her Hand writing, to publi&s;h her <HI>Name</HI> and <HI>Cure.</HI> And if any Per&s;on de&s;ires further Satisfaction in this matter, if they plea&s;e to enquire at her Brother's Hou&s;e, Mr. <HI>Percival</HI> in <HI>Benbridge-&s;treet,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of St. <HI>Giles</HI>'s in the Fields, this Fact will be atte&s;ted by Word of Mouth.</P>
<PB N="69" REF="70">
<P><HI>Samuel Maynard,</HI> dwelling in <HI>Lydes</HI> Court near St. <HI>Giles</HI>'s Church, being &s;orely afflicted with the Cholick, and Rheumati&s;m, the <HI>Sciatic&agrave;,</HI> and exce&s;&s;ive Pains in his <HI>Back</HI> and <HI>Limbs,</HI> in&s;omuch that he was uncapable of following his Employment, was happily cured by my Advice and taking my Reme|dies, in a very &s;hort time, and now is able to follow his Bu&s;ine&s;s as formerly. This Example I in&s;ert, as I could do many others, to &s;hew what a concatenation of Di&s;ea&s;es and <HI>different</HI> &s;orts of Pains and in many Places do often accompany this Di&s;ea&s;e, as will further appear in the next In&s;tance.</P>
<P>A &s;ufficient and reputable Trade&s;man's Wi&s;e, in the City of <HI>London,</HI> was un&s;peakably troubled with <HI>Vapours,</HI> originally proceeding from <HI>this</HI> Di&s;ea&s;e, which run her into <HI>Di&s;|traction;</HI> and after much Advice and taking many Medicines from other Phy&s;icians, to no purpo&s;e, her Husband &s;ent for me, and by Heaven s Ble&s;&s;ing, my particular Care, and the &s;ea&s;onable U&s;e of my Medicines, &s;he was re&s;tored to her <HI>Sen&s;es,</HI> perfectly <HI>re|covered,</HI> freed from her <HI>Vapours,</HI> and &s;o con|tinues. So that you &s;ee violent Pains of the <HI>Head, Giddine&s;s</HI> and <HI>Frenzies,</HI> are concomi|tants in a <HI>Caeliack Cholick.</HI> I will direct any mode&s;t Enquirer, how, and where, they may be &s;atisfied of the truth of this re|markable In&s;tance from the Gentlewomans own Mouth.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Cho|lerick Cho|lick.</NOTE>This Di&s;ea&s;e named in Greek <GAP DESC="foreign"> and in Latin <HI>Cholerica Pa&s;&s;io,</HI> is a Grier, in which the <HI>Vicious</HI> Humours are impetuou&s;ly thrown
<PB N="70" REF="71">out both by <HI>Vomit</HI> and <HI>Stool,</HI> with a violent Pain in the <HI>Stomach</HI> and <HI>Belly,</HI> Di&s;ten&s;ion of the <HI>Hypocondria,</HI> Heartburnings, Thir&s;t, Perplexity of the Brea&s;t, a &s;wift and &s;ome|times <HI>Small Pul&s;e,</HI> frequent <HI>Swoonings,</HI> a cold|ne&s;s in the outward Parts, <HI>Pro&s;tration</HI> of Strength, and at la&s;t <HI>Convul&s;ions</HI> and <HI>Hiccoughs.</HI> This Di&s;ea&s;e, &s;ome &s;ay, is a Symptom of the <HI>Expul&s;ive Faculty</HI> being hurt by uncocted Meats, and if the <HI>Retentive</HI> Faculty is al&s;o in fault, the Di&s;temper is &s;o much the wor&s;e and more violent.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Immedi|ate Cau&s;es of a Cho|lerick Cho|lick.</NOTE>Some make two &s;orts of this Di&s;ea&s;e, a <HI>Wet</HI> and a <HI>Dry,</HI> and from hence came the vulgar Di&s;tinction of <HI>Moi&s;t</HI> and <HI>Dry Gripes.</HI> A <HI>Moi&s;t</HI> is what I am di&s;cour&s;ing. The <HI>Dry</HI> is more rarely found, proceeds from a <HI>Windy</HI> Spirit, produced in the Stomach, by the fiery Heat of the part corrupting the Meat, or by Meats Rank and Windy, as <HI>Hipocrates</HI> him&s;elf affirms. <HI>Senuertus</HI> from the <HI>Hermeti|cal</HI> Doctrine, adds another <HI>cau&s;e,</HI> namely, Salt and adu&s;t Humours in the <HI>H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">pochondria,</HI> which grow Hot by the mixture of ano|ther Humour, and demon&s;trates it, by the mixing <HI>Aqua Fortis</HI> and <HI>Oil of Vitriol</HI> with <HI>Salt of Tartar,</HI> which produce very <HI>flatuous</HI> Spirits: So that according to the&s;e Authors, the <HI>Immediate</HI> Cau&s;es of this Di&s;ea&s;e, are, Cholerick, Burnt, Sharp, Salt or Rotten Humours of the <HI>Stomach, Bowels, Spleen</HI> and <HI>Me&s;entery;</HI> or &s;ome <HI>Nouri&s;hment</HI> of a per|nicious Quality, or &s;ome &s;trong Medicine or Poi&s;on, taken uncorrected.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">O<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">a&s;ional Cau&s;es.</NOTE>The <HI>Occa&s;ional</HI> Cau&s;es of a <HI>Cholerick Cholick,</HI> are the &s;ame with tho&s;e of a <HI>Loo&s;ene&s;s.</HI> The Corruption and Acrimony of <HI>Food</HI> in the Stomach, the <HI>a&s;&s;umption</HI> of Sharp, Co&s;tick
<PB N="71" REF="72">Medicines, &s;uch as <HI>Antimony,</HI> Ar&s;enick, Mer|cury, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
<P>If the Excrements are Livid, Faetid, Black, or <HI>Corro&s;ive;</HI> if it accompany Malignant <HI>Fe|vers,</HI> e&s;pecially in the Beginning, and if the Stomach is much <HI>di&s;ordered,</HI> it generally proves <HI>fatal.</HI> 'Tis an Acute Di&s;ea&s;e, and quickly fini&s;hes its Cour&s;e. It ob&s;erves a <HI>Tertian</HI> Period in its <HI>Exa&s;perations,</HI> and fre|quently <HI>relap&s;es</HI> after an apparent Cure.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms.</NOTE>The Signs preceding this Di&s;ea&s;e, are, frequent and plentiful <HI>Evacuations</HI> of Cho|lerick, &s;harp and corrupted Humours, up|ward and downward, &s;welling with <HI>Wind,</HI> Thir&s;t, and gnawing <HI>Pains</HI> in the Stomach and Guts: A Loathing, which a little ap|peas'd with <HI>cold Drink,</HI> which is &s;oon after ca&s;t up. The <HI>Pul&s;e</HI> high and unequal, <HI>Sweating,</HI> with Convul&s;ion of the extreme <HI>Parts</HI> and Swooning, are dangerous Symptoms. 'Tis ea&s;ily di&s;cover'd whether the Di&s;ea&s;e came by &s;ome violent Medicine, Poi&s;on, or of|fen&s;ive Dyet.</P>
<P>The <HI>Internal</HI> Cau&s;es are known by the <HI>Quality</HI> of the Humours that are ejected. If there be continual Loathing and Gnawing, the Di&s;ea&s;e is in the <HI>Stomach.</HI> If a Malignant <HI>Fever</HI> is join'd, it is in the <HI>Veins.</HI> If it has its Original from &s;ome ill Diet, there is <HI>Hopes,</HI> that when the peccant Matter is ca&s;t out, the Di&s;ea&s;e will end. If its very vio|lent, 'tis dangerous, for the greater the Con|vul&s;ions, Swoonings, and Coldne&s;s of the extream Parts are, the <HI>nearer</HI> Death is at Hand.</P>
<P>In the <HI>Beginning</HI> of the Cure, you ought to a&s;&s;i&s;t <HI>Evacuations</HI> with gentle, cooling, and clean&s;ing Cly&s;ters, e&s;pecially <HI>Milk</HI> Cly&s;ters,
<PB N="72" REF="73">with <HI>Venice Treacle,</HI> or <HI>Dia&s;cordium</HI> di&s;&s;olved in them are always u&s;eful. It's proper to <HI>breathe</HI> a Vein, to cool the burnt and boiled Blood, but let it be done with Di&s;cretion, Twice or Thrice, if the Strength be not impaired by the Fir&s;t. Endeavour to qualify the &s;harpne&s;s of the Humours after this manner. <HI>Waters of Plantane, Pur&s;lane and Mint of each two Ounces: Syrup of Quinces, and dried Ro&s;es, of each one Ounce; Syrup of Vinegary, half an Ounce, mix them, and di&s;&s;olve therein two Scruples of Theriack Andromachi, and &s;ix Drops of Oil of Vitriol:</HI> Give now and then a Spoonful. But if the Patient has &s;ome <HI>Ea&s;e,</HI> and if the Symptoms abate or di&s;appear, take great care that they dont <HI>&s;uddenly</HI> return, to your Amazement and the De&s;truction of the Patient, as it &s;ometimes happens <HI>unfore&s;een</HI> in this Ca&s;e. Therefore Nouri&s;h him and Strengthen his Stomach, &s;ays mo&s;t of our Eminent Phy&s;icians, with a Re&s;toring <HI>Opiate,</HI> compounded in or after this Method. <HI>Gelly of Harts-Horn made with Canary Wine, four Ounces, Con&s;erve of Ro&s;es, Burrage, Buglo&s;s and Clove Gilly-Flowers, of each one Ounce: Confectio Alkermes, half an Ounce, Citron Bark and Nutmegs, Candied, of each three Drams; E&s;&s;ence of Cloves, Mace, Nutmegs and Cinamon, of each three Drops, and with the Syrup of Clove Gilly-Flowers make On Opiate;</HI> of which mu&s;t be taken the quantity of a Hazle Nut or more, Mornings and Even|ings. Of all the Medicines u&s;ed again&s;t <HI>Loo&s;ene&s;s,</HI> &s;ays a great Author, <HI>Opium</HI> is the chief, being a powerful controler of all tumultuous Motions and accordingly pre|&s;cribes <HI>Laudanum Opiatum,</HI> or <HI>Liquid Lau|danum</HI> in large quanties, for the Cure of this and mo&s;t other Di&s;ea&s;es.</P>
<PB N="73" REF="74">
<P>But for my part, tho' I won't pretend to <HI>cen&s;ure</HI> the Practice of my Superiors, yet I think my &s;elf obliged to &s;ay, that I tamper not with <HI>Opiates,</HI> nor ever u&s;e <HI>Laudanum</HI> but on extraordinary occa&s;ions, being rather a <HI>Pallative</HI> than a <HI>Curative</HI> Medicine; and therefore in my <HI>Practice</HI> for the Cure of this or any other Di&s;ea&s;e I pretend to Cure, I only employ my own <HI>Experiencd</HI> Medicines, which by their own native <HI>vertue</HI> &s;ubdue Di&s;ea&s;es by their <HI>amicable</HI> corre&s;pondence with <HI>Nature,</HI> and by a&s;&s;i&s;ting her in all her <HI>Operations</HI> and <HI>endeavours,</HI> to &s;upport her <HI>&s;elf,</HI> and <HI>exterminate</HI> tho&s;e noxious Invaders, that di&s;turb her de&s;ired Peace and tranquility. And that I have &s;uch <HI>efficacious</HI> Remedies for the Cure of this Di&s;ea&s;e, if timely con|&s;ulted, will appear by the following Ex|amples.</P>
<P>An Eminent <HI>Trader</HI> in the City of <HI>Lon|don,</HI> who had for a long time been grie|viou&s;ly troubled with <HI>intollerable</HI> Pains pro|ceeding from a <HI>Cholerick Cholick,</HI> &s;uch as vio|lent Pains in the <HI>Stomach</HI> and Bowels, di|&s;ten&s;ion of the <HI>Hypochondria,</HI> Heart burn|ing, Thir&s;t and <HI>perplexity</HI> of the Brea&s;t; in|&s;omuch that he &s;carce enjoyed one Minutes Health, and having advi&s;ed with the Learn|ed, and taken a Multiplicity o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Medicines both <HI>inwardly</HI> and by <HI>outward</HI> applications to his <HI>Brea&s;t,</HI> to his very great trouble, but without Relief, he was at la&s;t recommended to me, and I perfectly cured him in a few Days, no <HI>Symptoms</HI> of the &s;aid Di&s;ea&s;e ha|ving <HI>appeard,</HI> &s;ince the time of his Reco|very; and tho' he is unwilling to have his Name expo&s;ed in <HI>Print,</HI> yet to do me and
<PB N="72" REF="75">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="73" REF="76">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="74" REF="77">my Remedies <HI>ju&s;tice,</HI> and that others might reap <HI>Benefit</HI> by the &s;ame means, he has or|der<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d me to &s;end any Per&s;on to receive Sa|tisfaction from his own Relation, which I am always ready to do.</P>
<P>Mr. <HI>John Shadwel,</HI> near the Sign of the Three <HI>Mariners,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of St. <HI>Thomas Wapping,</HI> Mate of a Merchant Man, having been a <HI>long</HI> Voyage, and feeding much up|on Meat that had been <HI>long &s;alted,</HI> at his comming on &s;hore, was violently taken with frequent <HI>vomiting</HI> and <HI>Purging,</HI> attended with great <HI>Weakne&s;s</HI> of Body, a <HI>chilne&s;s</HI> in the out|ward Parts and <HI>unexpre&s;&s;ible</HI> Pain. He con|&s;ulted two Phy&s;icians, took the Medicines they jointly pre&s;cribed, but tho&s;e Gentlemen being <HI>frighted</HI> at the appearance of a <HI>&s;light convul&s;ive Motion in the Patients Face and Eyes,</HI> gave him over as <HI>Incurable:</HI> Whereupon I was &s;ent for, and by the Ble&s;&s;ing of God upon one <HI>&s;ingle</HI> Medicine, he had Ea&s;e in le&s;s than Ten Minutes time, and continuing the <HI>&s;ame</HI> Medicine but four Days together, was perfectly Recovered, and &s;o remains to this Day.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Dy|&s;entery or Bloody Flux.</NOTE>A <HI>Dy&s;entery,</HI> which the Greeks name <GAP DESC="foreign">, properly &s;o called, proceeds from the Ulceration of the Inte&s;tines, but is commonly taken for <HI>every</HI> Bloody Flux: The Latins call it <HI>Tormina</HI> from the exce&s;&s;ive Pain the Patient endures. This Di&s;ea&s;e which is voiding <HI>Blood</HI> and <HI>purulent</HI> Matter with tormenting Pain, is di&s;tingui&s;hd from the Painle&s;s Evacuation of Thin, Watery Blood from the internal <HI>Hemerroid</HI> Veinsm, called by the Ancients a <HI>Flux</HI> of the <HI>Liver,</HI>
<PB N="75" REF="78">and likewi&s;e from the Natural di&s;charge of Blood independent of the Guts, causd by its redundancy in the Body, as after <HI>Ampu|tation,</HI> &s;uppre&s;&s;ion of the <HI>Men&s;es, &amp;c.</HI> or by its <HI>Acrimony</HI> opening the Ve&s;&s;els, or the Ob&s;truction of the <HI>Bowels</HI> hindering its re|gular Circulation. Agreeable hereunto, <HI>Galen</HI> mentions four kind of <HI>Fluxes,</HI> all which he calls <HI>Dy&s;enteries.</HI> The fir&s;t is when any <HI>u&s;ual</HI> Evacuation of Blood, as the <HI>Hemer|roids,</HI> or at the <HI>No&s;trils</HI> is impeded. Secondly, When <HI>Watery</HI> Blood is voided, occa&s;ion'd by the Weakne&s;s of the <HI>Liver.</HI> The Third is, <HI>Blood</HI> mix'd with <HI>melancholly</HI> and burnt by rea&s;on of its being <HI>detaind</HI> in the <HI>Liver</HI> and <HI>Spleen</HI> is evacuated and <HI>&s;hines.</HI> The Fourth and la&s;t, and that I am now treating of, is, when <HI>Blood</HI> and <HI>Excrements</HI> are mix'd toge|ther, and &s;ometimes al&s;o <HI>purulent</HI> Matter accompanies it, to the Patient's intolerable Pain.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Symptoms of a Dy|&s;entery.</NOTE>The <HI>Diagno&s;tick</HI> Signs of the <HI>Bloody-Flux,</HI> are, that the Sick Per&s;on is &s;eized with <HI>un|&s;ufferable</HI> griping Pains in the Guts followed by frequent <HI>Stools,</HI> fir&s;t of <HI>Whiti&s;h</HI> Matter, and afterwards of <HI>Blood</HI> and <HI>Slime</HI> mix'd to|gether. Watching, Thir&s;ting, loathing Food, and &s;ometimes attended by a Malignant Fever and all its <HI>di&s;mal Symptoms.</HI> If the Small Guts are affected, the Pain is <HI>vehement,</HI> like the pricking of <HI>Pins,</HI> becau&s;e they are of exqui&s;ite Sen&s;e: The Patient goes not to Stool pre&s;ently after the Pain, and when he does, is grievou&s;ly tortur'd, and the <HI>Guts</HI> and <HI>Bowels</HI> &s;eem to fall down. If the Great Guts are affected, the Pain is <HI>not &s;o</HI> &s;harp, and being &s;eated toward the &s;ides of the Belly, is quickly followed by Stools; the
<PB N="76" REF="79"><HI>Blood</HI> &s;wims on the top, or is a little mixd with the Excrements, and you may judge of the Humour cau&s;ing this Di&s;ea&s;e, by the <HI>Colour</HI> of the Excrements, Age and <HI>Tempera|ment</HI> of the Patient and the <HI>Sea&s;on</HI> of the Year.</P>
<P>There are Three degrees ob&s;ervable in a <HI>Dy&s;emery.</HI> The Symptoms of the fir&s;t are <HI>Bloody</HI> and <HI>Slimy</HI> Stools. In the Second, the <HI>Slime</HI> is a Sign of <HI>Excoriation</HI> and in the third of an <HI>Exulceration.</HI> When the Guts are <HI>Excoriated,</HI> 'tis either the <HI>Cru&s;t</HI> that co|vers them, or part of their thick <HI>Tunicle,</HI> or at mo&s;t the <HI>Caruncles,</HI> or inflamed <HI>Glandules</HI> of the Guts that is voided.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Progno|&s;tick Sym|ptoms.</NOTE>A <HI>Dy|&s;entery</HI> caus'd by <HI>black</HI> Choler is a dangerous Sign, if it be not Critical, becau&s;e the Ulcer grows <HI>Cancerous;</HI> be &s;ure there|fore you make a right judgment between <HI>melancholly</HI> and <HI>congeal</HI>'d Blood. If loathing of Meat and a <HI>Fever</HI> accompany it, 'tis dangerous. If Pieces of <HI>Fle&s;h</HI> be voided in it, 'tis Deadly. Much Watching, great Thir&s;t, Black Bloody and Stinking Stool<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">, without a mixture of Humours, Hiccough, Cholerick Vomitings, Pains in the <HI>Liver</HI> and <HI>Midriff,</HI> are generally deadly Signs. If <HI>Choler</HI> and &s;harp Diet is the Cau&s;e of this Di&s;ea&s;e, its <HI>ea&s;ily cured;</HI> Salt <HI>Phlegm</HI> is wor&s;e, becau&s;e <HI>&s;ticks</HI> longer in the Guts. If the becau&s;e it <HI>&s;ticks</HI> longer in the Guts. If the <HI>Bloody Flux</HI> happens to one troubled with a <HI>di&s;ea&s;ed Spleen,</HI> or the <HI>Gout,</HI> its good, in the Opinion of <HI>Hippocrates,</HI> becau&s;e the Matter is &s;ent forth. But I rather take this for a <HI>Diarrhea</HI> than a <HI>Dy&s;entery.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cau&s;es of the Bloody Flux.</NOTE>The <HI>Internal</HI> Cau&s;es of this Di&s;ea&s;e are &s;harp and <HI>&V;lcerating</HI> Humours. Yellow Green, and Black <HI>Choler;</HI> Salt Phlegm in the
<PB N="77" REF="80">Head created by <HI>Heat,</HI> or in the Belly by <HI>Putrefaction.</HI> which being brought to the Guts, and &s;ticking clo&s;e to them Ulcerates the Part. The &s;harp <HI>Acid</HI> that irritates the Guts, provokes them to <HI>Contraction,</HI> a&s;&s;em|bles the Blood by vertue of its provocation, and corrodes the <HI>Orifices</HI> of the Blood Ve&s;&s;els. This may proceed from the corrupted <HI>Mat|ter</HI> in the Guts. But the cau&s;e of a <HI>Malig|nant, Epidemical, contagious Loo&s;ene&s;s,</HI> &s;uch as the Learned <HI>Sydenham</HI> di&s;cour&s;es of, as hap|pening in the Years, 1669, 70, 71, 72, is a corrupt <HI>volatile Acid,</HI> not lodg'd in the Guts, but immediately reigning in the <HI>Blood,</HI> per|verting its <HI>Texture,</HI> opening the Ve&s;&s;els <HI>in|&s;erted</HI> into the Guts and <HI>provoking</HI> them to Convul&s;ive Contractions; from whence is derived a Malignant <HI>Fever, Griping and Bloody Stools:</HI> So tho' the <HI>previous</HI> excoriations may take place in <HI>benign</HI> Dy&s;enteries, there is no occa&s;ion for them in the <HI>contagious</HI> Ma|lignant &s;ort; it being a &s;ufficient Cau&s;e of <HI>bloody</HI> Stools, that the <HI>Co&s;tick</HI> Ferment is a Mortal Enemy to the Inte&s;tines, like <HI>Ar&s;e|nick,</HI> that perpetually thwarts and provokes them to <HI>Convul&s;ions;</HI> upon which, &s;ays that excellent <HI>Author,</HI> they &s;queeze out their <HI>Blood</HI> together with their <HI>Nutritious</HI> Juice, that they are not then in a capacity to re|ceive; and which is taken by &s;ome for the <HI>Mucus</HI> or Snot of the Guts, whereas the large quantities that are voided, &s;ufficiently evince the contrary.</P>
<P>The <HI>External</HI> Cau&s;es, are all &s;uch things as procreate &s;harp and ill Humours, as Meats which &s;oon putrify ill the Stomach, <HI>Fruits</HI> which are &s;oon rotten, and all things <HI>un|ripe:</HI> The Air thus qualified; the Winter
<PB N="78" REF="81"><HI>co'd</HI> and <HI>dry,</HI> and the Spring very <HI>Wet</HI> and full of <HI>South</HI> Winds, cau&s;e <HI>Dy&s;enteries</HI> in Sum|mer. Or if the Winter be <HI>Wet</HI> and full of <HI>South</HI> Winds, and a <HI>dry</HI> Spring, and the <HI>North</HI> Winds blow much; &s;uch a Sea&s;on generally &s;peaking produces <HI>Bloody Fluxes.</HI> Sometimes the Air is infected and produces a Conta|gious and <HI>Epidemical</HI> Dy&s;entery, which is &s;o infectious, that the <HI>Excrements</HI> of the Sick being ca&s;t into a <HI>Bog-hou&s;e,</HI> infect, all that &s;it over it. To which may be added, the taking of <HI>Mercury, Coloquintida, Antimony, Lead,</HI> the cour&s;e Pouder of an <HI>Adamant, Worms, &amp;c.</HI> which vellicate the Guts and heap up &s;harp Humours in them.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">To Cure of the Bloody Flux.</NOTE>From what has been already &s;aid, you may rationally infer, that Indications for Cure of a <HI>Dy&s;entery,</HI> are, to evacuate <HI>&s;harp</HI> Humours, a&s;&s;wage <HI>Pain,</HI> Clean&s;e, Con&s;oli|date and Dry the <HI>&V;lcers,</HI> Purify the <HI>Blood,</HI> &s;eparate the preternatural <HI>Ferment</HI> and &s;top the <HI>Flux.</HI></P>
<P>To di&s;charge the Body of &s;harp Humours you mu&s;t Purge every Second, Third or Fourth Day, according to the Patient's <HI>Age</HI> and <HI>Strength,</HI> and the <HI>Sea&s;on</HI> of the Year. <HI>Rhubarb</HI> given in Pouder <HI>a Dram, a Dram and half, and two Drams</HI> is very u&s;ual; but becau&s;e <HI>Pouders</HI> are apt to &s;tick to the <HI>Guts</HI> and vex them, I better approve of it converted into a <HI>Potion,</HI> made of <HI>Liquoras, Rai&s;ms of the Sun, Tamarinds and yellow Myrabolans</HI> boiled in <HI>Bar|ley-Water, to Three or Four Ounces;</HI> which Li|quor being <HI>&s;trained,</HI> infu&s;e in it a Dram of <HI>Rhubarb</HI> &s;liced very thin; then add an Ounce of <HI>Syrup of Ro&s;es Solutive,</HI> and you have a very good Medicine to <HI>evacuate</HI> &s;harp Humours.</P>
<PB N="79" REF="82">
<P>If the <HI>Dy&s;entery</HI> is accompanied with a <HI>Fever</HI> and Inflamation of the <HI>Bowels,</HI> open a <HI>Vein,</HI> let the Patient Bleed in proportion to his <HI>Strength.</HI> Sometimes vomiting is pro|fitable, to repel the Humours, which fall from the <HI>Stomach</HI> to the <HI>Inte&s;tines,</HI> and there|fore not to be omitted, e&s;pecially if the Pa|tient is <HI>inclined to Vomit,</HI> for then Nature <HI>dictates</HI> the right way, and ought to be im|mitated, in <HI>disburdening</HI> a foul Stomach. Afterward you ought to give <HI>a&s;&s;waging,</HI> mild and clean&s;ing Cly&s;ters, and &s;ucceed them with <HI>A&s;tringent</HI> Cly&s;ters.</P>
<P>If the <HI>&V;lcerss</HI> &s;tand in need of <HI>clean&s;ing,</HI> add <HI>Centaury</HI> and <HI>Wormwood</HI> to the former De|coction, and to the &s;trained Liquor add <HI>Tur|pentine di&s;&s;olv<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d in the Yolk of an Egg, and the Chymical Oil of Wax, of each one Dram.</HI> When there is more need of <HI>Binding</HI> and Gluti|nating Medicines, give <HI>Empla&s;tick</HI> Cly&s;ters, to cover the internal <HI>Superfices</HI> of the Guts, and pre&s;erve tho&s;e Parts from the <HI>Gnawing</HI> of the Matter.</P>
<P>To clean&s;e, give <HI>Goats Milk;</HI> to glutinate <HI>Cows Milk</HI> Chalybeated, which is proper to con&s;olidate and <HI>heal,</HI> to which you may add the Juice of <HI>Plantan, Syrup of Comfrey, Sugar of Ro&s;es, Troches of Amber, and Rha&s;is's white Troches.</HI> Let the Sick eat <HI>Rice boiled in Cha|lybiated Milk, or the Mucilage of Gum, Traga|canth and Arabick, drawn with Ro&s;e or Plantan Water, the quantity of half a Dram in his Broath.</HI> To purify the Blood and &s;eparate the pre|ternatural Ferment, <HI>Goddards Drops are often &s;ucce&s;sful.</HI> And to <HI>compleat</HI> the Cure, the Body being throughly clean&s;ed you may u&s;e <HI>A&s;tringent Decoctions and Narcoticks to &s;top the Flux.</HI></P>
<PB N="80" REF="83">
<P>And if this <HI>Cour&s;e</HI> and the&s;e <HI>Medicines</HI> are ineffectual, as &s;ometimes to the Patient's di&s;appointment and extravagant Charge, they have been too often found; let the Sick <HI>try my</HI> Medicines, which have never yet <HI>failed</HI> to cure the <HI>Bloody Flux,</HI> in nu|merous In&s;tances, of which I only give you <HI>Two</HI> Examples.</P>
<P>Mr. <HI>Alexander Carter,</HI> Taylor, dwelling in <HI>Swan-Yard,</HI> over again&s;t <HI>Somer&s;et-Hou&s;e</HI> in the <HI>Strand,</HI> was &s;orrowfully afflicted with the <HI>Bloody-Flux</HI> above two Years together, with|out any <HI>Intermi&s;&s;ion,</HI> in&s;omuch that he had almo&s;t <HI>ruin'd</HI> him&s;elf in going from one Do|ctor to another, and yet was &s;till rather <HI>wor&s;e</HI> than any thing <HI>better,</HI> till he came to me and made u&s;e of my Remedies, which cured him in a few Days, and now continues in as good Health, as ever he enjoyed in his Life. To the truth whereof he is ready to make Oath, if de&s;ired.</P>
<P>Mr. <HI>Thomas Chiffinch,</HI> Carpenter, Aged <HI>Sixty</HI> odd Years, was <HI>Seven</HI> Years grieved with the <HI>Bloody Flux</HI> at certain Times; but the la&s;t Three Years had it con&s;tantly, and in &s;o violent a manner as threatned him with inevitable Death, in the Opinion of all his Friends and Acquaintance; for he could find no <HI>Relief</HI> in all the means he u&s;ed: But applying him&s;elf to me, and taking my Medicines, was cured in a &s;hort time, and at a &s;mall Charge; the truth of which im|mediate Cure, will be atte&s;ted to any Per|&s;on, that plea&s;es to enquire either of Mr <HI>Clark,</HI> or the Patient him&s;elf, at <HI>Duglas</HI>'s-<HI>Coffee</HI> Hou&s;e in St. <HI>Martin</HI>'s <HI>Lane, We&s;tmin&s;ter.</HI></P>
<PB N="81" REF="84">
<P>Having now, I pre&s;ume, &s;aid enough a|bout the Cure of the <HI>Cholick</HI> in all its <HI>dif|ferent</HI> kinds, and the other Di&s;ea&s;es that generally <HI>accompany</HI> it, &s;ufficient for the <HI>In|&s;truction</HI> of the Indu&s;trious and <HI>Ingenious,</HI> and too much for the <HI>Envious</HI> Idle and Ignorant, I &s;hould have concluded this <HI>Treati&s;e,</HI> but becau&s;e I re&s;olve to publi&s;h &s;everal <HI>other</HI> Di&s;cour&s;es on other Di&s;ea&s;es, and that many People who have met with repeated <HI>Di&s;|appointments</HI> in following other Mens <HI>Reme|dies,</HI> before my <HI>Books</HI> now under Hand can be Publi&s;h'd; for <HI>their</HI> &s;akes as well as <HI>my</HI> own, I &s;hall briefly &s;hew, in a few <HI>Examples,</HI> in what other Di&s;ea&s;es as well as the Cho|lick, my Medicines have been <HI>wonderfully</HI> &s;ucce&s;sful, and al&s;o that the over <HI>curious</HI> or <HI>&s;u&s;picious</HI> may receive entire Satisfaction, by enquiring of the <HI>Per&s;ons</HI> I have taken leave to Name, and the Places where they dwell, in the following brief <HI>Catalogue,</HI> which I &s;hall begin with the <HI>Head-Ach.</HI></P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Head-Ach and Ver|tigo.</NOTE> <HI>William Fletcher,</HI> of <HI>Engfield,</HI> in the <HI>Country of Middle&s;ex,</HI> White-Smith, being grie|vou&s;ly afflicted with the Megrim, Gid|dine&s;s and Swimming Pains in the Head, &s;o that oftentimes he was in danger of falling down as he Work'd or Walk'd, which con|tinued upon him for the long &s;pace of Six Years, and u&s;ing divers Medicines for his Cure, but without Succe&s;s; he applied to me, and I in letting him Blood in the in&s;ide of one of his No&s;trils, and giving him a Medicine, he found immediate Relief, without any Pain or Trouble for above a Year; but afterwards finding a
<PB N="82" REF="85">Pain and Giddine&s;s, on the other &s;ide of his Head, and I letting him Blood in the No&s;tril of that &s;ide, he was perfectly Cured of that Vexatious and Trouble&s;ome Di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Head Ach.</NOTE>Mr. <HI>Samual Haines,</HI> Broad-Silk-Weaver, dwelling in <HI>Fa&s;hon-&s;treet,</HI> in <HI>Spittle-Fields, London;</HI> was for the long &s;pace of Twelve or Thirteen Years, violently afflicted with the <HI>Head-Ach,</HI> and tho' he indu&s;triou&s;ly &s;ought Relief from other Hands, could find none, till he made u&s;e of my Remedies, and by them, the Almighty's Ble&s;&s;ing in|terpo&s;ing, was <HI>thoroughly</HI> cured.</P>
<P><HI>Edward Harri&s;on,</HI> Leather Dre&s;&s;er, living with Sir <HI>I&s;aack Shard,</HI> Knight, in <HI>Hor&s;e-lye-Down,</HI> near <HI>Southwark,</HI> was &s;orely afflicted with the <HI>Head-Ach</HI> at certain times, which return'd very often, and continued to his great Chief in this manner <HI>Six</HI> whole Years &s;ucce&s;&s;ively, of which he could find no Cure, tho' he u&s;ed <HI>variety</HI> of Medicines from no mean Profe&s;&s;ors of Phy&s;ick; but at la&s;t ap|plying him&s;elf to me, was perfectly cured.</P>
<P><HI>Margaret Thomas,</HI> Servant to the late Mrs. <HI>Jux,</HI> who was her Maje&s;ty's <HI>Strower,</HI> and did then dwell in <HI>Little Scotland-Yard,</HI> ad|joining to <HI>White-Hall,</HI> was grievou&s;ly troubled with the <HI>Head-Ach</HI> for the &s;pace of Two Years, and with other <HI>Female</HI> Di&s;tempers much longer, with which &s;he will acquaint any of her own Sex, that think-fit to en|quire of her; but after the u&s;e of not a few Medicines pre&s;cribed by other Practitioners
<PB N="83" REF="86">in Phy&s;ick, without effect; &s;he was reco|vered from all her Di&s;ea&s;es by following my Advice, and the u&s;e of my <HI>Medicines,</HI> and continues in perfect Health to the pre|&s;ent time.</P>
<P><HI>William Wat&s;on,</HI> late Servant to Mr. <HI>Welch,</HI><NOTE PLACE="marg">Vertigo.</NOTE> a Shoe-Maker, in <HI>Chancery Lane, London;</HI> was much troubled with a <HI>Vertigo,</HI> or <HI>Gid|dine&s;s of the Head,</HI> between Five and Six Years, and &s;ometimes &s;o violently, that &s;ome thought it would terminate in a <HI>Ap|poplexy</HI> or <HI>Epilep&s;y,</HI> of which Di&s;ea&s;e he could find no Cure, till he applied him&s;elf to me, and by God's Ble&s;&s;ing, and giving him <HI>Ex|perienc'd</HI> proper Remedies, he was re&s;tored to Health.</P>
<P><HI>Mo&s;es Grant,</HI> late Servant to Mr. <HI>London,</HI> Perruke-Maker, in <HI>Channel Rowe, We&s;tmin&s;ter,</HI> was Fourteen Years troubled with the <HI>Head-Ach,</HI> and <HI>Four Years</HI> la&s;t pa&s;t, was af|flicted with it in &s;o grievous a manner and with &s;uch intolerable Pain, without <HI>one Days</HI> intermi&s;&s;ion; and making u&s;e of divers Me|dicines without Relief, he came to me, and I effectually cured him by giving him my Medicines in <HI>Six or Eight times,</HI> and he has continued well for a Year la&s;t pa&s;t, as he a&s;&s;ures me, excepting <HI>twice</HI> that he was &s;lightly vi&s;ited with it, by too <HI>hard</HI> Drink|ing, which &s;oon went off again, without the u&s;e of any means.</P>
<P>A Child of Mr. <HI>John Evans</HI>'s, Frame-Work-Knitter, in <HI>Hand-Alley,</HI> in <HI>Bi&s;hops-Gate-&s;treet,</HI> was &s;o grievou&s;ly afflicted with <HI>&s;ore-Eyes,</HI> occa&s;ion'd by a Defluction of
<PB N="84" REF="87"><HI>Hot Rheum</HI> on tho&s;e tender Parts which con|tinuing with great &s;everity above a Quarter of a Year, 'twas the general Opinion &s;he would be <HI>Blind;</HI> but her Father addre&s;&s;ing him&s;elf to me, I perfectly cured his Childs <HI>Sore Eyes,</HI> and took away the Cau&s;e in Three or Four Days time, and left her as well as ever &s;he was in her Life.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Worms</NOTE>Mr. <HI>Robert Guinn,</HI> at the Sign of the Two <HI>Brewers,</HI> in <HI>White Lyon Yard,</HI> near <HI>Norton-Falgate,</HI> in the Pari&s;h of <HI>Stepney;</HI> for &s;ome Years pa&s;t was &s;o abundantly Pe&s;ter'd with <HI>Worms,</HI> that &s;ometimes they drop'd out of his Body as he went along the <HI>Streets,</HI> and at other times crept from him when he was in <HI>Bed.</HI> He was al&s;o afflicted with an Exce&s;&s;ive <HI>Ravenous Appetite,</HI> and yet tho' he Eat as much as would have &s;ufficed <HI>Six</HI> or <HI>Eight</HI> Per&s;ons, he received no <HI>Nouri&s;hment</HI> by his Food, but fell away, and was &s;o wa&s;ted in his <HI>Fle&s;h,</HI> that he was little el&s;e than <HI>Skin</HI> and <HI>Bones.</HI> He had long &s;ought Relief from many, and variety of means, but all in vain, till he came to me, and through <HI>Mercy</HI> I cured him of all the&s;e <HI>complicated</HI> and <HI>uncommon</HI> Di&s;tempers, in about a Fort|nights time; and has continued in a good &s;tate of Health ever &s;ince.</P>
<P>The Son of Mr. <HI>John Carter,</HI> in <HI>George-Alley,</HI> in <HI>Coleman-&s;treet, London,</HI> who was a|bout Two Years of Age, and terribly af|flicted with <HI>Worms,</HI> and gnawing griping Pains, by taking my <HI>Remedies,</HI> voided above a <HI>Pint of Worms,</HI> was freed from his Pains, and has continued well ever &s;ince.</P>
<PB N="85" REF="88">
<P>I could give you may other in&s;tances of Per&s;ons of both Sexes, Young and Old, but I re&s;erve them for a particular <HI>Treati&s;e</HI> of the <HI>Worms,</HI> that will immediately follow the publication of this Book.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Rheuma|ti&s;m and Gout.</NOTE>A Gentleman of con&s;iderable Quality, Lame with a <HI>Rheumati&s;m</HI> and the <HI>Gout</HI> to &s;uch a degree, that he dreaded the utter lo&s;s of the u&s;e of his <HI>Limbs;</HI> but applying him&s;elf to me, I cured him of his <HI>Rheumati&s;m,</HI> eas'd his <HI>Arthritick</HI> Pains, and &s;o re&s;tor'd the u&s;e of his Limbs, that he is capable of attending his own Affairs: And tho' he will not allow his Name to be <HI>Printed,</HI> yet I have his leave to &s;end any Per&s;on to him, who will confirm the Truth of what is here but <HI>privately</HI> di|vulg'd. To Name more Per&s;ons whom I have cured of the <HI>Rheumati&s;m,</HI> is wholly needle&s;s, &s;ince the Weekly Papers have from time to time, publi&s;h'd to many. And tho'. I don't pretend to m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ke a perfect Cure of the <HI>Gout,</HI> yet I hope I may be allowed to &s;peak truth, and &s;ay, That my Medicines never <HI>fail</HI> to give &s;peedy <HI>Ea&s;e</HI> in the mo&s;t violent <HI>Pains</HI> attending that Di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Stone &amp; Gravel.</NOTE>Mr. <HI>William Cordwell,</HI> Frame-Work-Knitter, at the Sign of the <HI>Black-Boy,</HI> in <HI>Wheeler</HI>'s-<HI>&s;treet, Spittle-Fields,</HI> being violently afflicted with <HI>Suppre&s;&s;ion of &V;rine,</HI> occa&s;ion'd by the <HI>Stone, Gravel,</HI> and a concommitant <HI>Cholick,</HI> which had continued at certain Times for Three Years la&s;t pa&s;t, and &s;ince <HI>Chri&s;tmas</HI> la&s;t in a more <HI>&s;evere</HI> manner than ever; applied him|&s;elf to me, and by the u&s;e of my Remedies aforenamed, voided &s;everal <HI>Stones</HI> and ob|tain'd a perfect Cure: And having paid me
<PB N="86" REF="89">for my Medicines to my own content, de|&s;ired al&s;o, that his <HI>Cure</HI> might be publi&s;h'd, that others labouring under the &s;ame Di|&s;temper, might receive Benefit by the &s;ame Hand and Means.</P>
<P><HI>Francis-Wilks,</HI><NOTE PLACE="marg">Fevers.</NOTE> dwelling near the Sign of the <HI>Black-Hor&s;e,</HI> in <HI>Blackman-&s;treet,</HI> hard by St. <HI>George</HI>'s-Church, in <HI>Southwark,</HI> was &s;eize Five Months with a <HI>Tertian Ague,</HI> and having taken great quantities of <HI>Je&s;uit</HI>'s Powder, or <HI>Peruvian Bark,</HI> and an incredible number of other Medicines, to no purpo&s;e; in&s;omuch that he &s;eem'd to be on the <HI>Brink</HI> of the Grave, and his Circum&s;tances being but <HI>in|different,</HI> I offer'd him his Cure <HI>Gratis,</HI> which I perform'd with great <HI>Expedition,</HI> and &s;o <HI>effectually,</HI> that after the <HI>fir&s;t</HI> Do&s;e of Phy&s;ick I gave him, his <HI>Fit</HI> return'd no more, and the Patient enjoys his Health to this Day.</P>
<P>The great number of <HI>Patients</HI> I have cured of <HI>Fevers,</HI> under all Denominations, whether attended or unaccompanied with a <HI>Cold &s;haking Fit,</HI> which are vulgarly call'd <HI>Agues,</HI> will excu&s;e me from giving more Examples in this Di&s;ea&s;e, becau&s;e my Medicines, are &s;o well known to give relief in <HI>Fevers,</HI> that to commend them by Te&s;timonies in un|ce&s;&s;ary wa&s;te of time, &s;ince they <HI>recommend</HI> them&s;elves by their <HI>Innate</HI> Vertue; not be|cau&s;e they are <HI>Hot,</HI> not becau&s;e they are <HI>Cold,</HI> not becau&s;e they <HI>Cut</HI> and attenuate; but becau&s;e they have the <HI>peculiar</HI> vertue, to ex|tingui&s;h the <HI>hot fermenting Alkali,</HI> which is the <HI>Occa&s;ional, Internal and Continent cau&s;e of Fevers,</HI> and that they may effect what they are de&s;ign'd for, I vary them as I find Oc|ca&s;ion;
<PB N="87" REF="90">becau&s;e, <HI>vix ulla perpetua Ars Medici|nalis recepit,</HI> &s;carce any of the Precepts of the Art of Phy&s;ick are perpetual.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Coughs and Con&s;um|ptions.</NOTE>Mr. <HI>Thomas Adin,</HI> Weaver, dwelling in <HI>King</HI>'s-<HI>Head-Yard,</HI> in <HI>Shore-Ditch,</HI> was long afflicted with a <HI>Con&s;umptive Cough,</HI> attended with all the <HI>di&s;mal</HI> Symptoms of approaching Death; but by the ble&s;&s;ing of God, the Me|dicines I directed him to take, perfectly re|covered him.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Spitting Blood.</NOTE> <HI>Mary,</HI> Wife of Mr. <HI>Richard Darling</HI> Barber, formerly dwelt in <HI>Burchen-Lane,</HI> near <HI>Lum|bard &s;treet, London,</HI> was in Three Years time la&s;t pa&s;t, twice cured by <HI>Medicines</HI> of a vio|lent <HI>Cholick</HI> and <HI>Spitting Blood,</HI> and the la&s;t Spring was &s;eized with a <HI>Hectick Fever,</HI> and all the dreadful Symptoms of an approach|ing <HI>Tabes</HI> or <HI>Con&s;umption,</HI> and was given over for a <HI>Dying Woman</HI> by all her Friends and Relations; but by Heaven Ble&s;&s;ing the <HI>Me|dicines</HI> &s;he took of me, &s;he was re&s;tored to her former Health, as will be atte&s;ted by more than <HI>Twenty</HI> Eye-Witne&s;&s;es of her <HI>un|expected</HI> Cure, as well as by the <HI>Patient</HI> her &s;elf.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The French Di&s;ea&s;e.</NOTE>In the next place I could give many Ex|amples of Per&s;ons I have cured of both Sexes, of <HI>Gonorheas</HI> and the <HI>French Pox;</HI> but becau&s;e to give <HI>Examples</HI> in &s;uch Ca&s;es, would be a <HI>horrid</HI> breach of <HI>good Manners;</HI> I &s;hall only recommend my <HI>Medicines</HI> as <HI>Safe</HI> and <HI>Certain</HI> in the <HI>Cure,</HI> and my &s;elf for perfect Silence.</P>
<PB N="88" REF="91">
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Stone.</NOTE>The la&s;t Di&s;ea&s;e of which I &s;hall give any <HI>Examples</HI> in this Book is the <HI>Stone,</HI> and &s;hall begin in the well known Ca&s;e of Mr. <HI>Richard Hurford,</HI> at the Sign of the <HI>New England Arms,</HI> near <HI>Ratliff-Cro&s;s,</HI> who was Twelve Years afflicted with the <HI>Stone,</HI> but lately in a mo&s;t violent manner, and having taken abundance of <HI>Medicines</HI> in hopes of <HI>Ea&s;e,</HI> but all in vain, I gave him my own <HI>Medi|cines</HI> experimentally adapted to the Cure of that Di&s;ea&s;e <HI>in his Ca&s;e,</HI> which brought a|way an incredible number of <HI>Stones,</HI> and &s;ome of them as large as were capable of pa&s;&s;ing through the <HI>&V;reters</HI> and can &s;carce be credited by any, but tho&s;e that have &s;een and handled them.</P>
<P><HI>Mary,</HI> the Wife of Mr. <HI>Richard Pomfret,</HI> dwelling in <HI>Little Carter Lane,</HI> near the <HI>Swan Ale Hou&s;e,</HI> was afflicted with the <HI>Stone</HI> and <HI>Gravel</HI> to that degree, that upon any agi|tation of the Body &s;he made <HI>Bloody &V;rine,</HI> and after &s;he had had the Advice of &s;everal <HI>Doctors</HI> of Phy&s;ick, but without &s;ucce&s;s; the fir&s;t <HI>Remedy</HI> I gave her, put a &s;top to her <HI>Bloody &V;rine,</HI> and brought away a prodigious Quantity of <HI>Gravel,</HI> by which means &s;he was Cured at a &s;mall Charge, and in a very &s;hort time.</P>
<P>Having thus plainly <HI>proved</HI> to the meane&s;t Capacity, the <HI>efficacy</HI> of my <HI>Remedies</HI> the <HI>Sincerity</HI> of my Practice, and the <HI>Truth</HI> of the Examples of Per&s;ons cured, in&s;omuch that they that are not blinded by <HI>partiality</HI> or by|a&s;s'd by <HI>Intere&s;t,</HI> mu&s;t be Ma&s;ters of a great deal of <HI>Sophi&s;try,</HI> that will pretend to deny, contradict or oppo&s;e them. I &s;hould now put an end to this brief Di&s;cour&s;e.</P>
<PB N="89" REF="92">
<P>But having a little Paper to &s;pare I &s;hall employ it, in accommodating the Reader with the <HI>Vertues</HI> and <HI>&V;&s;e</HI> of a bitter Medi|cament, which I invented, and call <HI>Tinctura Stomachicalis major,</HI> or <HI>the greater Stomachical Tincture.</HI></P>
<P>Which is a Compo&s;ition of all the Noble&s;t <HI>Bitter</HI> Aromatick and Stomachical Specificks in the whole <HI>Materia Medica,</HI> and perfectly an&s;wers all Intentions accordingly. It enlivens and &s;harpens a languid <HI>Appetite,</HI> expels <HI>Vi&s;cous</HI> Humours; a&s;&s;i&s;ts <HI>Fermentation</HI> and helps <HI>Di|ge&s;tion;</HI> Fortifies the <HI>Stomach</HI> and prevents <HI>Nau&s;eating</HI> and Loathing. It is <HI>Carminative,</HI> a great expeller of <HI>Wind</HI> out of the Stomach and Bowels; and as all bitter things are Me|dicinal again&s;t <HI>Worms,</HI> &s;o this <HI>Tincture</HI> has an excellent faculty that way. If any Per&s;on has the misfortune to drink <HI>bad</HI> Wine, or to drink to <HI>exce&s;s;</HI> if he mingles &s;ome Drops of this Tincture in his Wine, it will rectify all <HI>Di&s;orders</HI> occa&s;ion'd by hard Drinking, and prevent next Mornings <HI>Head-Achs,</HI> loath&s;ome <HI>Vomitings,</HI> and menacing <HI>Surfeits,</HI> the u&s;ual Attendants on Nocturnal Debauches. It's a good Remedy for Per&s;ons newly deliver'd from a <HI>Fever,</HI> or any <HI>Chronical</HI> Di&s;temper, be|cau&s;e it &s;trengthens the <HI>Cra&s;is,</HI> or convenient mixture of Qualities. It's proper for <HI>Ma|riners</HI> to carry with them to Sea, and for tho&s;e that Travel by <HI>Land,</HI> becau&s;e it prevents ill accidents occa&s;ion'd by <HI>Ill</HI> or <HI>Scanty</HI> Diet, change of <HI>Air,</HI> and Epidemical <HI>Infections.</HI> It far excels all other <HI>bitter</HI> Medicaments; it never offends the Eyes, or cau&s;es breakings out on the Skin, as generally all other <HI>Bitters</HI> do. It will keep good many Years, and may be taken in <HI>Wine, Ale, Tea, or Spring-Water,</HI>
<PB N="90" REF="93" MS="y">from Thirty Drops to a Hundred, in the Morning, and at Four or Five of the Clock in the Afternoon, when People find occa&s;ion for it, either to <HI>cure</HI> Di&s;ea&s;es, <HI>prevent</HI> them, or <HI>confirm</HI> one in a State of good Health, in which I have found my <HI>Tincture</HI> &s;ucce&s;sful in many Years Practice; being as plea&s;ant a <HI>Bitter</HI> as Art can contrive. <HI>One</HI> Ounce of Mine will make <HI>Three</HI> Ounces of any other <HI>Bitter,</HI> that is commonly expo&s;ed to <HI>Sale.</HI> And that the Poor may receive Benefit by it, I will Sell it to &s;uch as really are &s;o, for Two Shillings the Ounce, and Twelve Pence the Half Ounce.</P>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">T<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters"> u<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters"> of th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> C<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">pta|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="3 letters"> Sn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="MURP" EXTENT="2 letters">.</NOTE>For the Cure of the <HI>Head-Ach,</HI> Deafne&s;s, Vertigo or Giddine&s;s, and the Cure of an Old and Inveterate Cough, I have al&s;o a <HI>Caephalik Snu&s;h,</HI> which &s;nuffed up both No|&s;trils, Night and Morning, till the No&s;e runs plentifully, will produce the de&s;ired Effect; but when this and other Remedies fail, as the be&s;t &s;ometimes do; I have ano|ther way of curing the <HI>Head-Ach,</HI> and <HI>Ver|tigo,</HI> by <HI>Phlebotomy,</HI> in the Part, and by a &s;afe Method &s;carce known, or practis'd by any other Per&s;on.</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
